INSERT INTO `applications` VALUES (439,'0016-03-14','Rebeccah','Pailes-Friedman','rpf@getinterwoven.com','','www.getinterwoven.com','','','','Industrial Design','','I am a leader in the field of smart textiles and wearable technology.  I have recently published a book, Smart Textiles for Designers,  and have lectured all over the world on both smart textiles and the research I have done for NASA in wearables and the integration of technology into the objects we wear.   At Pratt, where I have been of the faculty in both the Fashion and Industrial design departments for over 15 years, I have created numerous classes around design, research and innovation including collaborations with Ubiquitous Computing at UNH, NYU-Poly\'s Interactive Engineering and Sensor Design at Stony Brook  as well as the co-taught Mars Transit Habitat Design with Pratt Architecture.\n \n In 2014, I founded Interwoven Design Group, an industrial design and innovation consulting practice specializing in wearable technology and smart textiles.  We develop products for clients and created installations for museums and galleries.  We split our work between research and consumer products and enjoy work that involves new materials, technology and the physical body.  As a designer and artist, I am concerned with both aesthetics and the human condition, at Interwoven our work raises questions about the future and  the boundaries of communication through fashion, design and technology. \n \n Since starting Interwoven, we have received a commission to create a work for the My Shirt is Breathing show at the Biet Ha\'ir Museum in Tel Aviv Israel in 2015 and currently have work on tour with the Coded Couture show currently at the Pratt Manhattan Gallery in NYC.  We are in the midst of working on a smart textile installation, ICEBERG,  exploring how e-textiles and fiber based technologies can be crafted to provoke thought bringing awareness to an individual\'s exposed data.\n \n Interwoven would be an asset to New Lab as a smart textile and wearables expert.','','','1.  Wondering what types of sewing equipment you currently have.  Do you have industrial sewing machines, straight stitch, zig zag, merrow, etc industrial irons, no sew machines (welding, seam seal etc.) and any types of machine knitting machinery.  If not I own some of this equipment and have access to it at other places but would like to see what you have on site in addition to any other of the RP equipment that we use in our practice.\n \n 2. Also, I have applied previously and had a couple emails back from you but i see you already have tenants and wondering when I will be contacted for an interview or at a minimum a tour.','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:07','2016-03-26 00:06:07'),(440,'0016-03-08','Shmuel','Branover','sbranover@ha-col.com','','www.ha-col.com','','','','Connected Hardware','','I am a EE freelancer, based in Brooklyn.  I specialize in designing, developing and building electronic prototypes and proof of concepts. Most of my work is for early stage startups with limited resources. I have a basic workshop set up in a garage in Crown Heights. ','','','I am interested in your prototyping facilities and how do members get access to them.','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:07','2016-03-26 00:06:07'),(441,'0016-03-08','David','Menicovich','david.menicovich@gmail.com','','www.actasysinc.com','','','','Energy','','We\'re a platform company specialized in Active Flow Control. Our technology enables energy efficiency by enhancing aerodynamic performance without changing the shape of objects such as heavy vehicles, buildings and turbine blades.  We\'re currently operating in the heavy vehicle industry have entered recently into the smart buildings industry and plan to expand to wind turbine near term. Our work is interdisciplinary and multi faceted in nature. Our adaptive system includes hardware and software and combines novelties in applied smart materials, acoustics and active flow control techniques with big data analytics. We are seeking a work environment that is multidisciplinary to be involved in and  contribute to.','','','No questions','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:07','2016-03-26 00:06:07'),(442,'0016-03-03','Donnel','Baird','Donnel@blocpower.org','','www.blocpower.org','','','','Energy','','We are a growing clean energy startup, focused on developing a range of software, project finance, and analytics solutions for deploying clean energy projects in financially underserved NYC neighborhoods. We will develop 1-2000 clean energy projects in Brooklyn over the next 3 years, and can also serve as a platform for other innovative clean energy companies.','','','We have short term space needs and are very interested in being a long term tenant, and part of the community. What might be possible? We look forward to meeting ASAP!','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:07','2016-03-26 00:06:07'),(443,'0016-03-01','Jason','Green','jason@edenworks.org','','www.edenworks.org','','','','Urban Tech: Food & Agriculture','','Edenworks develops and operates vertical indoor aquaponic farms. We grow uncompromisingly delicious and sustainable salads. \n \n We\'ve been operating an R&D greenhouse facility in Bushwick for 2 years, selling produce to early adopters like Maple. We\'re looking for a space to expand and deploy our flagship commercial facility. Our anchor customer is a major grocer who will be rolling out our product for retail across NYC.\n \n We learned about New Lab from the EDC, who relayed that New Lab has some raw space in addition to the finished + manufacturing space. We\'re very interested in learning more about the former for production and the latter for office + R&D.','','','What does rent / membership cost for Urban Tech Hub? What does rent cost for the raw space? How soon will both be available for tenancy?','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:07','2016-03-26 00:06:07'),(444,'0016-02-29','Andrew','Chee','ac@collectiveassembly.com','','http://andrewchee.com/','','','','Consumer Products','','Formally trained in computer science and music, self-taught designer, maker of algorithmically generated objects including CNC furniture and artist\'s books, while commissioned by user interface, systems, and installation design for a roster of private clients. I feel that design in all of its increasingly hybrid qualifications (interaction, graphic, print, architectural, etc.) should follow and build upon the progress and processes of open-source hardware and software. Looking to collaborate with like minds on projects for- and not-for-profit. Seeking the space, shared equipment, and collective energy that fosters similar and larger goals. Some of my work is here: http://andrewchee.com/ + http://collectiveassembly.com/.','','','General curiosity regarding the range of membership fees, start dates, and generally what the practices are of your larger community, if there are any similarities and/or good matches for collaboration? Also would be great to see a detailed list of shared lab equipment, particularly a CNC, laser cutter, and perhaps a SLA 3D printer? Thank you!','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:07','2016-03-26 00:06:07'),(445,'0016-02-25','Thomas','Kosbau','thomas@venawater.com','','www.venawater.com','','','','Urban Tech: Air/Water Quality','','I\'m an architect and an entrepreneur that founded www.oredesign.org, http://www.growenergy.org/, and VENA Water.  We are currently producing prototypes for VENA water\'s technology in our incubator space in California because we don\'t have access to prototyping equipment in New York, but would like to keep our creative capital localized.  \n \n About VENA: VENA\'s AWG has the smallest carbon footprint of any water deliverance technology on the market. VENA\'s AWG eliminates the use of energy intensive condensing mechanisms found in conventional AWG technologies. By eliminating moving parts, mechanical mechanisms and energy intensive refrigerants to generate water, our AWG requires minimal maintenance and operational costs. By providing low energy, local and sustainable water to water scarce regions, our AWG is the least expensive AWG on the market today. Once each unit is constructed, VENA\'s AWG will produce water through the system\'s lifespan.\n \n VENA\'s AWG architecture is designed to minimize materials and construction while optimizing performance and cost. Our system\'s architecture is design to be able to be constructed with local materials and equipment. We use commercially off the shelf products (COTS) to comprise each system component. Through remote satellite sensors and monitoring technology, VENA is able to measure continuous performance, advising local maintenance personnel on effective maintenance practices to ensure optimal functionality. However VENA\'s passive AWG design contains no moving parts, mechanical mechanisms or harmful refrigerants, requiring minimal maintenance and cost to local communities.','','','I\'m most interested in access to prototyping equipment.  As a member of New Lab would the machines be free or subsidized for our use?  \n \n Thanks,\n \n Thomas','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:07','2016-03-26 00:06:07'),(446,'0016-02-19','Kelsey','Libner','kels@fastmail.com','','kels.info','','','','Other','','Hello,\n I am a freelance user experience designer and am interested in solo coworking. I am currently actively developing an online product, but it is in an early stage and success is not guaranteed.\n \n I live in Clinton Hill, not far from you.\n \n Is there coworking space available for a singleton like myself?\n \n Kelsey Libner','','','I already know something about New Lab because I\'ve toured the Navy Yard and also had a conversation with Scott whom I met at a professional event (can\'t remember which).','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:07','2016-03-26 00:06:07'),(447,'0016-02-19','Charles M.','Doomany','contact@charlesdoomany.com','','http://charlesdoomany.com','','','','Other','','Project Blog (Instagram): https://instagram.com/chuck_makes/\n 2015 Research/Project Portfolio: http://charlesdoomany.com/dlPort.php?file=Doomany_Portfolio_2015\n *Industrial Design and Product Development Client Case Studies available upon request\n \n I am a product designer with a complementary background in prototyping, engineering, and visual design. I hold a double Masters in Innovation Design Engineering from the Royal College of Art & Imperial College London (MA/MSc) and a Bachelors in Industrial Design from Carnegie Mellon University (BFA).\n \n I am interested in realizing products and tools that spur radical change, innovate, and inspire a vision for the future through a tactful marriage of technology and design. I also believe in \"validation through making\" as a fundamental approach to the design process - using prototyping as a tool for communicating, informing, and advancing a design through direct feedback with the world.\n \n Aside from my product development and industrial design work, my research interests/topics include: applications granular materials, aggregate architecture, transformable materials and structures, decentralized/distributed manufacturing, and multi-property material innovation.','','','• Do you have multi-material 3D printing capabilities?\n • Do you expect to have any design or fabrication job openings at New Lab in the near future?\n \n Thank you. I am also interested in scheduling a Private Tour of the New Lab space.','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:07','2016-03-26 00:06:07'),(448,'0016-02-18','Varun','Adibhatla','varun@argolabs.org','','argolabs.org','','','','Connected Hardware','','Hello NewLab! ARGO Labs is a nascent UrbanTech R&D organization pioneering a civic data science through an integrative framework of Device, Data & Decision-making. Our mission is to partner with city agencies to co-create scalable citywide solutions through rapid prototyping.  We believe that embracing such an approach would yield in unlocking many digital solutions for NYC and beyond. ARGO Labs, in the flesh,  is Varun Adibhatla and Graham Henke who are recent graduates of NYU\'s Center for Urban Science and Progress, (Class of 2015) along with a coalition of like-minded Urban informatics practitioners and current CUSP students.\n \n Our flagship project, Street Quality Identification Device (SQUID) is a low-cost sensor platform to perform autonomous street surveys using a GPS, accelerometer, and camera to provide a visual ground truth to street inspections and optimize resource allocation. Today, NYC spends upto $300 million a year on maintaining its streets and is liable to hundreds of millions of $$ in settling tort claims from defective roadways. The city relies on 311 complaints and manual techniques to react to degrading streets. SQUID empowers the city to be proactive about street maintenance in a way that was not possible before.\n \n Even a 1% optimization to street resurfacing decision making would more than pay for SQUID and result in a cost savings from data-driven & preventative maintenance. SQUID\'s mantra is that in order to connect the dots, you have to first collect the dots.  SQUID was a finalist at NYC Big Apps, 2015 and a recipient of a Knight prototype grant.\n \n With the emergence of LinkNYC - we are confident that we are well suited for the emerging urban tech environment to solve intractable city problems using device, data and decision-making and would fit right in with with NewLab\'s mission, resources and contribute to its community.','','','Do we need to have  a business plan to strengthen our application ? We ask this because the space we operate in at times, challenges conventional \"startup-wisdom\".','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:07','2016-03-26 00:06:07'),(449,'0016-02-14','MARK','GARDNER','MARK@JAKLITSCHGARDNER.COM','','WWW.JAKLITSCHGARDNER.COM','','','','Built Environments','','WE ARE WORKING WITH A NON-PROFIT ON A SOCIAL IMPACT ENTERPRISE WITH GLOBAL BEEKEEPERS. IT IS GROWING INTO AN OFFSHOOT FROM THE ARCHITECTURAL | DESIGN PRACTICE. I AM INTERESTED IN HAVING A FLEXIBLE SPACE TO NETWORK WITH INDIVIDUALS AND START-UPS WITH A LIKEMINDED SOCIAL CAUSE.','','','I AM INTERESTED IN GETTING MORE SPECIFIC INFORMATION ON THE HUB AS IT BECOMES AVAILABLE.','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:07','2016-03-26 00:06:07'),(450,'0016-02-12','Jason','Hardy','jason@unender.com','','unender.com','','','','Other','','I\'m an Executive Design Director for Odopod (www.odopod.com) and recently relocated from San Francisco to New York City. At Odopod I led large teams of visual and UX designers, developers, strategists and content creators to design complex digital initiatives for some of the world\'s most innovative companies.  I\'ve worked on digital products for Tesla, SpaceX, Google, EA, Hawaiian Airlines, LeapFrog and many others. I am also a contract designer for The Criterion Collection, a company based in NYC that releases classic and important films on DVD, BluRay and digitally. I design cover art, materials and am currently working on a number of new exciting projects for them. \n I love San Francisco and always will, but I came to New York to seek out new opportunities and to be inspired by new communities. I\'m interested in using technology to enrich the peoples\' lives. To create useful products that deserve to exist. I\'m not interested in rhetoric and blind ambition. I believe in art, I believe in empathy, I believe in honesty and I believe in rolling up ones sleeves and getting to work. \n New Lab seems like a place where I might find some like-minded people. A place where I can contribute to the culture, to share my experience and expertise and to grow as a creative individual.','','','No questions, the site does a pretty good job of communicating the purpose of the space. ','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:07','2016-03-26 00:06:07'),(451,'0016-01-18','Arpita','Dey','pitadey@gmail.com','','www.arpitadey.com','','','','Consumer Products','','I am working on a smartphone app and a line of smartphone attachments that will make designing and installing solar either as an individual property owner or as a community more efficient and fun.\n\nI am a mechanical engineer and software developer. I am currently working on a software application that connects potential solar customers with local solar installers and provides both parties with the tools (for site assessment, 3D drawing and making financial projections) needed to make installing solar easier, more transparent, more efficient and as profitable as possible for the property owner. Along with the application itself, I will need to design and manufacture a line of smartphone attachments (which I am excited to rapidly prototype via additive tech) that will make shading analysis easier for solar installers. And if all of this proves useful to anyone, I have grand plans to manufacture our own line of solar modules...but that\'s quite a ways off :). So I guess I am an engineer and an entrepreneur. But I\'d rather say engineer because entrepreneur can mean anything including unemployed indefinitely :) and I still do client work when I want to.','','','How do I apply to the Urban Tech Hub program?\n\nWhat do you imagine your pricing will be for the smallest studio space you offer? And for coworking space? Also are you still on schedule for opening this summer-ish? And when is the soonest an interested party would be able to take a tour of the space?\n\nThanks so much!\nArpita','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:07','2016-03-26 00:06:07'),(452,'0016-01-12','Ebby','Amir','get@ebby.nyc','','www.ebby.nyc','','','','Consumer Products','','I\'m an engineer, designer, and interactive storyteller. My projects include web and VR experiences, film and photo productions, and artist collaborations. I devise my own projects and also create experiences for companies like Refinery29 and VICE.','','','I\'d love to discover more about the space and see how it can be used as both a working space and a studio space for producing multimedia projects.','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:07','2016-03-26 00:06:07'),(453,'0016-01-07','Tim','Kreukniet','tim.kreukniet@ev-box.com','','www.ev-box.us','','','','Energy','','EV charging for commercial locations.\nNL headquartered company.\nBrooklyn office covers North America.\nAssembly now in Virginia - contemplating move to the city (if finances allow it)','','','Would like to have a meeting to talk about office and assembly potential for EV-Box.\nCurrently 4 Fte and in the Urban Future  Lab.\nMight want to do assembly in Brooklyn (if it works with Start-up NY and financially, quality control)','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:07','2016-03-26 00:06:07'),(454,'0016-01-06','Maxwell','Fine','max@mpowerd.com','','www.mpowerd.com','','','','Consumer Products','','MPOWERD is a Manhattan based B-corp that develops and sell a family of solar inflatable lanterns called the Luci.  Our mission is to empower the 1.5 billion people living without electricity in developing countries.  Create innovative and affordable products to help people use clean energy in their daily lives. The more we sell in the developed world, the more we can reduce costs in the developing world. Our light is a cleaner, safer, more affordable option in the developing world where people need it most.','','','Hi, \nOur team is looking for an innovative space to grow. We currently have 20 employees and we are looking for 3,000 - 3,600 square feet.  Our team hold 10 utility and design patents worldwide and our team is constantly working to develop new innovative consumer products. Our customers include: WalMart, REI, Staples, Clinton Foundation, and many others to name a few.\nOur target moving date is June 2016.\nThank you,\nMax','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:07','2016-03-26 00:06:07'),(455,'0016-01-06','Ro','Gupta','ro@carmera.co','','carmera.co','','','','Connected Hardware','','Carmera is a road intelligence platform for smart cities and the future of transit. We build and deploy connected sensors on vehicles that regularly traverse the city to generate high definition, high temporal resolution \"ground truth\" imagery for mapping, location and predictive analytics markets. These markets cut across transportation, urban planning, infrastructure, SMB commerce and other industries.\n\nJustin Day (x CTO @ MakerBot/co-founder @ Blip.tv) and Ro Gupta (x VP/data lead @ Disqus) are the co-founders of Carmera. The company is based in Brooklyn, NY and backed by investors such as Resolute Ventures, Notation Capital, Joe Montana and Bre Pettis.','','','Hi there,\n\nWe are currently working out of NYC Resistor but looking for our own space in Q2 that could fit 7 employees, and eventually 10+ and would have easy parking or garage access since we work on vehicles and will have our own by then. \n\nWe\'d love to learn more and perhaps schedule a visit  to see if NL might be a good fit for us, and vice versa.\n\nThanks and best of luck with the opening.\n\nRo','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:07','2016-03-26 00:06:07'),(456,'0015-12-20','Darya','Dubouskaya','darya.dubouskaya@gmail.com','','https://www.linkedin.com/in/darya-dubouskaya-4a64a390','','','','Robotics','','I\'m currently working in CityTech in Emerging Media Major as well as I\'m working with Electrical and Telecommunications Engineering Technology Department.  I\'m currently a senior student and will graduate in Spring 2016. I do a creativity of a  new technology, prototyping, 3D printing, 3D modeling, programming, electrical and mechanical engineering.','','','I would love to be a part of new lab as the idea of new lab is exactly what i do in a college: creating new technology, prototyping, 3D printing, 3D modeling, programming, electrical and mechanical engineering. I\'m very good at creating ideas and building prototype of it, bringing inspiration to developers and meaning in the project by making it innovation, simple for user and new in it\'s industry.','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:07','2016-03-26 00:06:07'),(457,'0015-12-01','Seth','Hillinger','seth@rd11.com','','http://drops.nyc','','','','Connected Hardware','','AudioDrops is a social playlist for the places you go. It introduces a new way to experience the world using location technology, enabling anyone leave and discover music anywhere. We embody the spirit of play while allowing for deep connections between people, place, music and memory. We created a location-based experience that doesn\'t rely on plotting points on a map and believe AudioDrops will incentivize people to explore and connect with their world in delightful new ways.','','','Hi, just interested in learning more. Thnx!','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:07','2016-03-26 00:06:07'),(458,'0015-11-30','RICARDO','TOLEDO-CROW','rtoledocrow@gmail.com','','http://coldsteellaser.com/','','','','Medical','','We\'re a micro startup in medical devices. We\'ve been working with Honeybee Robotics for some time. Our expertise is in medical device development, physics, optics, micromechanics & microelectronics, and integrating all these elements with code.','','','We may be looking for a bench soon to continue development and it seems that Newlab would be a good environment.  Could we discuss the details of the  Newlab concept?','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:07','2016-03-26 00:06:07'),(459,'0015-11-25','Carlo','Van De Roer','cvdroer@gmail.com','','http://satellite-lab.com/','','','','Other','','I am an artist whose work explores the capacity imaging technology has to represent our world.\nI recently developed technology enabling, for the first time, the use of moving light sources within the frozen world of high-speed imaging.  \nTo further this technology, last year I started Satellite Lab, a new company sitting at the intersection of science and creativity, opening  up new doors for film-making, advertising and the arts. We recently received our patent for this technology and are coming out of a development phase as we ramp up to take on  projects.','','','I am currently a part time member of New Inc at the New Museum and heard about your program through a friend there, the mission of your project sounds inspiring, its great to see an organization making this effort!','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:07','2016-03-26 00:06:07'),(460,'0015-11-20','Noah','Feehan','nfeehan@gmail.com','','akamediasystem.com','','','','Connected Hardware','','Hi, I\'m an artist and researcher with a background in performance electronics, music interface design, CNC engineering, and art/art theory. More is at my website...','','','Hi, I\'m still a little while away from officially starting my first self-directed venture (I\'m currently senior creative technologist at the New York Times R&D Lab, where I run the hardware research division), but I\'m interested in meeting the folks who make New Lab their home.\nMy ideal next year would involve a really modest crowdfunded venture that proves out the manufacturability and utility of a product I\'ve been working on (a wearable that implements \"electrovibration\" technology, which dynamically changes the texture of a smooth pad). I\'m not fully comfortable with some aspects of startup world (lack of inclusivity, insane money-lust), but will probably try to find a way to navigate that world while still being true to my own ethics...','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:07','2016-03-26 00:06:07'),(461,'0015-11-18','Andrew','Zolty','aszolty@gmail.com','','brealfastny.com','','','','Connected Hardware','','I\'m the co-founder and Chief Creative Officer at BREAKFAST and Instaprint. I\'m considering starting a side project where I\'ll be designing and manufacturing small runs of bespoke connected products. It\'d artisan meets high tech.','','','I\'m mainly looking for a space to build and store materials. and products while having access to the tools I\'d need (CNC, laser, 3D printer, etc). I\'m open to a shared space or small private.','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:07','2016-03-26 00:06:07'),(462,'0015-11-03','Jeffrey','Cripe','cripe.jeffrey@gmail.com','','https://jeffreycripe.squarespace.com/','','','','Connected Hardware','','WHAT:  CarGo is building commercial consumer hardware for hired and shared vehicles. Our first product is a small, portable, electronic vending machine that sells convenience items (e.g. gum, advil, phone charger, headphones) to passengers. Once CarGo has distributed these devices through its car-service partners, it is well positioned to create an interconnected network of mobile wifi hotspots, and offer in-ride entertainment opportunities or location based promotions to passengers.  The possibilities for improving passengers\' lives are numerous and meaningful. \n\nWHY:  I am an Uber/Lyft/Gett etc. addict. I no longer take cabs, I no longer rent cars, I no longer use Zipcar. Neither do my friends. These app services improve my quality of life and save me money. Consequently I\'m in hired/shared cars daily, often looking for something I left behind, whether I\'m on the way to work, to the airport, or out at night. I\'m accustomed to having everything at my fingertips but in one of the places I spend the most time, I couldn\'t be further away.  I want to change that, for me, for everyone. \n\nPROGRESS: We will complete our first working prototype by the first week of December 2015. Currently, we have multiple major app-based car services on board to participate in a pilot phase once the machines are manufactured, and are in discussion with Enterprise Holdings about a major strategic investment and distribution relationship. We will complete our seed round by late January.','','','I am an entrepreneur, consultant, and employee of Christie\'s auction house who has spent the past 3 years in the fine art industry developing Christie\'s ecommerce business.  My partner is an industrial designer and mechanical engineer who lives blocks away from your space. \n\nWe would love to discuss joining  as members and would require minimal space to design and develop our hardware technology. We would also very much like to be involved and give back to the community you are creating!  \n\nQUESTIONS?\n-What are the membership economics?\n-Do you anticipate opportunities for cross-collaborations among artists, entrepreneurs, sponsors etc?\n-As you develop this space and community, how can we help? I am passionate about service and think this is a fantastic undertaking - if it\'s possible to get involved, I\'d love to.','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:07','2016-03-26 00:06:07'),(463,'0015-11-03','Karim','Naraghi','karim@wellsbi.com','','www.wellsbi.com','','','','Health','','We are building a digital platform to help individuals and small employers make more informed health insurance benefits decisions.','','','We are currently a group of 2 co-founders, likely to be expanding to 4 people by early 2016 seeking a co-working space in the Navy Yard area.','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:07','2016-03-26 00:06:07'),(464,'0015-10-26','Kevin','Lynch','kevin@crunchfund.com','','none','','','','Other','','I am currently working for an early stage venture firm in San Francisco while attending college at Claremont McKenna (physical location in LA)','','','I\'ve heard great things about you from a friend who worked with XPrize. Would love to hear more about the space and your plans for the future.','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:07','2016-03-26 00:06:07'),(465,'0015-10-22','Susanna','Choe','susanna.choe@consensys.net','','www.consensys.net','','','','Other','','Consensus Systems (ConsenSys) is a venture production studio building decentralized applications and various developer and end-user tools for blockchain ecosystems, focusing primarily on Ethereum. We are also working on a consulting basis helping large companies integrate the blockchain into their work across many different industries, as well as creating educational programs for people to learn about how to build apps on Ethereum. We would love to be able to collaborate with the kind of people and companies in the New Lab as we continue to build open source technology that will essentially catalyze social, economic and political change.','','','As the office manager, I would love to come by to check out your space before it opens up. I\'m wondering how much it would be to rent office space that would hold approx 15-20 people.','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:07','2016-03-26 00:06:07'),(466,'0015-10-18','Curtis','Paige','cpaige@paiteksys.com','','www.paiteksys.com','','','','Consumer Products','','We design electronic security systems and detection devices.','','','Cost?','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:07','2016-03-26 00:06:07'),(467,'0015-09-28','Che-Wei','Wang','cwwang@gmail.com','','cwandt.com','','','','Consumer Products','','We design products and make art.  We\'re aiming to become a full in-house on-demand manufacturing and design studio.  We spend half our time designing and bringing products to market and rest of our time making artwork.  Our work is sometimes based in hardware and sometimes in software.\n\nWe\'re super comfortable with a variety of manufacturing methods.  We\'re experienced with shopbots, haas cnc mills and lathes, waterjets,  a whole bunch of 3d printers ranging from makerbots to objet connex machines. We\'ve built our own lasercutter and plastic extruder.','','','A bunch of our friends are already new lab memebers. Jason Krugman, Jess Banks, David Benjamin,  Eric Foreman, are all good friends that we\'ve known for many years, so we\'re super familiar with new lab and we\'d love to become part of it!','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:07','2016-03-26 00:06:07'),(468,'0015-09-23','Dan','Lipski','lipski.tm@gmail.com','','www.danlipski.com','','','','Industrial Design','','I\'m a bicycle frame fabricator with a keen interest in cargo bicycles. Having studied at the United Bicycle Institute in Portland, OR, my focus has been on steel fabrication while I\'d eventually like to expand into other materials. I\'m one of a few dealers of the Larry vs Harry cargo bicycles (Copenhagen) in New York City which is an expanding and