in Brooklyn – my neighborhood','','','I am looking to interact and to collaborate with other designers, and to achieve great networking and create very wide projects from various disciplines.  am I applying to the right place?\nbtw...\nI am 40 years old....','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:07','2016-03-26 00:06:07'),(470,'0015-09-17','Robert','Steiner','bob.steiner@gmail.com','','https://www.linkedin.com/pub/robert-steiner/5/19a/a4b','','','','Additive Technology','','As Chief Product Officer at MakerBot Industries - Ran the Product Team from 2012 - 2014 and responsible for the Replicator, Replicator2/2X, Digitizer and Design Studio.','','','Interested to see what your set up will be for CNC (Wood/Metal) or 3D printing capabilities.   If there are plans to have a model shop for post processing (Painting/Model Building)?','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:07','2016-03-26 00:06:07'),(471,'0015-09-16','Kavodel','Ohiomoba','kavodel@fieldvision.co','','www.fieldvision.co','','','','Consumer Products','','We build intelligent cameras that automate the recording of sports and practices.  Simply turn it on with a mobile app and go.','','','I\'d love to be  a part.','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:07','2016-03-26 00:06:07'),(472,'0015-09-02','Mars','Cyrillo','mars@smartcanvas.com','','www.smartcanvas.com','','','','Other','','Smart Canvas was born with the goal of tackling \"Collaboration Paradox\"\n\nAccording to Forrester Research:\n\n> \"The success of any collaboration platform depends, in part, on the ability of the system to enable employees with a problem to connect with employees who can solve that specific problem. But so far, collaboration platforms have struggled to deliver on expectations because they exist inside a collaboration paradox — employees typically need to invest their own time to gain the benefit of the tool, but they are reluctant to invest the time without an immediate benefit.\"\n\nHierarchy aside, employees are usually organized in teams that will set out to solve problems to help the business. More often than not, some teams will solve problems that other teams had already solved in the past. Worse, some teams will barely communicate with adjacent teams with which they could otherwise discuss and develop breakthrough ideas. Generally, big companies have always generated silos and by breaking those silos companies can truly spark innovation potential.\n\nSmart Canvas allows teams to curate content for themselves, but will promote general-interest interactions and cross-pollination of ideas and discussions among teams inside the organization. The product will also use gamification and machine learning to identify relevant topics and automatically connect people looking for answers to other people who seem to be experts. Machine learning is also at the core of a \"nudge engine\" that keeps reminding people of the collaboration potential inside the company.\n \nWe got inspired by the simplicity of the \"online music\" apps, which have the incredibly hard goal to organize a huge database of content and tastes. The intersection of people and machine learning showed already to be a winner for the music industry and that has been our approach since we started to build Smart Canvas.','','','We are currently using WeWork downtown. We like it and we try to get the most our of it. As they say, “innovation happens in the space between” and we know that having the opportunity to bump up against others working to break down barriers and disrupt old ways of working will have an exponential impact on our product.\n\nWe believe that being in a truly multi-disciplinary environment like NewLab will help us to develop our product faster - not incrementally but by leaps and bounds. We also would love to power the platform that everyone in the lab could use to collaborate. This would be our biggest contribution to the NewLab environment - providing the canvas by which others more effectively work together. \n\nSmart Canvas is a future spin-off of CI&T (ciandt.com), a company born in Brazil, now with 2000 employees globally, and for two consecutive years, named by Google as Partner of the Year for Cloud Platform.  I am the person who leads our relationship with Google and our product efforts. I will be the CEO of Smart Canvas when we launch the product publicly in Q1/2015.','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:07','2016-03-26 00:06:07'),(473,'0015-09-01','John','Driscoll','jdriscoll@boston-engineering.com','','https://www.boston-engineering.co','','','','Other','','We are a VAR for PTC. We would like to discuss providing CAD/CAM/CAE, PDM/PLM, Keyshot , MathCAD and other product development tools along with online training for your starts up. \n\nhttp://www.ptc.com/','','','Please call me if you are interested.   781-484-6490 or Office 914-235-3528','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:07','2016-03-26 00:06:07'),(474,'0015-08-23','Pradeesh','Paraprath','pradeesh.ferrari@gmail.com','','www.ofmsuae.com','','','','Consumer Products','','I am  basically a post graduate in Manufacturing Management and running small business in United Arab Emirates. I heard about your space and thought  of using advantage of your facility to develop one product which i don\'t have the infrastructure here.','','','I would like to know the entire process and cost factors  to while using your facilities.','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:07','2016-03-26 00:06:07'),(475,'0015-08-15','Lucy','Beard','lucy@feetz.com','','www.feetz.com','','','','Additive Technology','','Feetz is the Digital Cobbler - reinventing traditional footwear manufacturing to make ultra-personalized footwear with your smartphone and a 3d printer. Funded by Khosla Ventures and Investors including ex-CEO Reebok and ex-CMO GAP.\n\nLooking to expand to NYC and seeking a community that understands making things, but in a new way, to make the next generation of the world a better place.','','','Interested to learn more about the space, sizing, ability to grow as company grows, pricing, and the community integration between other tenants','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:07','2016-03-26 00:06:07'),(476,'0015-08-12','Mike','Karp','mike@dogstar.life','','www.dogstar.life','','','','Connected Hardware','','We\'re building the world\'s first emotion tracking wearable for dogs.  We\'re MBA students from the first class at Cornell Tech, funded by Cornell, and partnered with the Cornell Vet School.','','','Just want to learn more!','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:07','2016-03-26 00:06:07'),(477,'0015-08-11','Francesca','Jones','francesca@lunaspower.com','','In stealth mode','','','','Energy','','Lunas Power Inc is bringing energy efficiency to the oil industry. Our proprietary electronic technology lowers the cost, carbon emissions, and environmental health risks associated with transporting heavy crude oil. While we\'ve demonstrated the process at bench-scale, we\'re currently working to develop a small, portable prototype.','','','Is there any price range available for the co-working memberships and for the 500 sq ft studio spaces? To start, we\'re interested in the co-working, but may also be interested in a small space.','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:07','2016-03-26 00:06:07'),(478,'0015-08-11','Jonathan','Stidd','jonathanstidd@gmail.com','','http://www.faucetfriend.us/','','','','Connected Hardware','','We make a suit of retrofit smart home devices that make this technology more accessible to consumers.  While smart home technologies offer tremendous benefits, their price and installation requirements act as a barrier to consumers.  For instance, automatic faucets save $100s per year in utilities, help the environment and offer convenience.  However, these devices are difficult to install (usually 1 hour) and expensive (average price $374).\n\nFaucet Friend solves this with a retrofit device that adapts to any faucet in minutes, for $60.','','','New Lab sounds like an amazing environment and community that I would love to be part of.  Please let me know when and how I can formally apply.  Thank you for your time!','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:07','2016-03-26 00:06:07'),(479,'0015-08-11','Michael','Mooring','mike@newspace.nyc','','http://newspace.nyc','','','','Other','','We\'re an incubator for outer-space startups in NYC. \n\nHoneybee Robotics and Final Frontier Design recently moved to the Brooklyn Navy Yard. At NewSpace NYC we want to further incubate the Navy Yard to become the \"space district\" of NYC.','','','What are the terms available?','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:07','2016-03-26 00:06:07'),(480,'0015-08-10','David','Baker','2015@davidbaker.tv','','davidbaker.tv','','','','Consumer Products','','Technical direction and application development for media companies in New York City.','','','Interested in coworking space for 2.','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:07','2016-03-26 00:06:07'),(481,'0015-07-27','Olivia','Koski','olivia@guerillascience.org','','guerillascience.org','','','','Education','','Guerilla Science create events and installations for festivals, museums, galleries, and other cultural partners. We connect people with science in new ways by producing live experiences that entertain, inspire, challenge and amaze.','','','We have small engineering art projects that we are looking for lab space for.','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:07','2016-03-26 00:06:07'),(482,'0015-07-27','Michael','Leach','michael@boardlab.com','','www.boardlab.com','','','','Consumer Products','','I\'m building a 3D interactive web app that will allow surfers to design their own surfboard fin online. A 3D model is then passed on to me for fabrication using robotic cnc milling technology. BoardLab\'s mission is to combine the interactive web with digital fabrication technologies to create a mass-customization business model for a niche product within the surf industry. I am an aerospace engineer and architectural designer by trade with a passion for 3D design and digital fabrication.','','','I\'ve been to New Lab\'s current space and was impressed with the design-focused entrepreneurs already working there. How will the new space accommodate for companies like mine using robotic cnc mills?  I also co-organize a design entrepreneurship meetup with over 600 members.  I would love to chat with someone about a potential event partnership to expose our members to what New Lab is doing.','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:07','2016-03-26 00:06:07'),(483,'0015-07-24','Kevin','Siwoff','kevin.siwoff@gmail.com','','http://kevinsiwoff.com','','','','Other','','I\'m an artist and technologist.  My work activates the relationship between people, light, and space. I create self-generating, adaptive systems using computation, often using the human voice as a catalyst. My background is in electrical engineering and data science, and I\'ve worked within the fields of physical computing and parametric/generative design.  I hold a Bachelors degree from NYU, and I currently teach in the graduate Integrated Digital Media department at NYU Polytech.  I was also part of New Inc\'s inaugural class.','','','Since most of my work involves the creation of large-scale lighting installations/sculpture, I\'m really interested in both the fabrication/shop space, as well as options for studio space.  My practice often involves digital fabrication techniques like laser cutting and 3D printing, and it would be great if I could access those resources at New Lab.  \n\nAdditionally, I feel that I\'m a very considerate community member, and I will actively contribute to an open and friendly culture!','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:07','2016-03-26 00:06:07'),(484,'0015-07-20','Julien','Deswaef','julien@xuv.be','','http://xuv.be','','','','Other','','Digital designer interested in cross media experiments and open source collaborative practices. Critical thinker, future tools builder and educator.','','','Living couple blocks away from your location, I would love to  pay a visit and discuss with you possibilities of organizing an open source product design workshop.','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:07','2016-03-26 00:06:07'),(485,'0015-07-15','Adam','Leeb','iam@adamleeb.com','','astrohaus.com, adamleeb.com','','','','Connected Hardware','','I am  a designer, engineer (MIT Alum) and  maker of things. One such thing is the Freewrite, a smart typewriter for distraction free writing. It was launched  on Kickstarter last year with worldwide success (340k+ raised) much to everyone\'s surprise. My team and I are opening an office in New York to expand our business and launch our product this fall.  I have heard about the New Lab and can\'t think of a better community to get involved with!','','','Please consider us for membership. We have a small, innovative team that would be a great fit.  Thank you!!','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:07','2016-03-26 00:06:07'),(486,'0015-07-02','Daniel','DAlonzo','daniel.dalonzo@gmail.com','','danieldalonzo.com - cooperativeimpact.com - princetonimpactproject.com - princeton.boutique - thestartup.university','','','','Education','','I am a social entrepreneur who aligns stakeholders from the community to create collective impact for the disconnected youth.','','','Hey - hope you are doing well. Lab looks incredible. Congrats on all of this so far.\n\nI have been developing the various components of a social enterprise ecosystem. I mobilized enough people here that it\'s moving on its own. I am getting ready to make a move to a city who is more welcoming to the ideas of social entrepreneurship. Looking for a nice place to settle into that would be welcoming to the  innovation.\n\nMay we please schedule a time for a quick call? I am flexible the rest of this week and early next week. How about this Monday at 4pm set?\n\nI appreciate your time, and I look forward to hearing from you.\n\nSincerely,\n\nDaniel DAlonzo\nCell: 908-358-4226','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:07','2016-03-26 00:06:07'),(487,'0015-07-01','Shaun','Salzberg','shaun.salzberg@gmail.com','','http://shaunsalzberg.com','','','','Consumer Products','','Hi New Lab, I\'m Shaun Salzberg, a recent MIT Media Lab grad and current Design Technologist at digital design firm Control Group. Professionally, I\'m a software engineer with a specialty in web and mobile development, but personally I\'m a designer, inventor, and entrepreneur with a 10-page list of both hardware and software ideas just itching to be built.  I\'m currently looking to make the leap to the freelance world as I continue to work on prototyping one of my more promising product ideas and building up a company around it. I\'m therefore on the search for studio space / shop space in the NYC area, and I\'d love to learn more about New Lab and visit the space. \n\nThanks! Please feel free to contact me at 732-718-9617 or shaun.salzberg@gmail.com to discuss further.\n\n- Shaun\n\nIn case you\'re interested, some current and past projects I\'ve worked on include:\nhttp://www.transitory.me/\nhttp://www.substringthegame.com/\nhttp://www.shaunsalzberg.com/medialab/fabclass/final\nhttp://www.shaunsalzberg.com/medialab/quarkz\nhttp://www.shaunsalzberg.com/medialab/periodic_table\nhttp://www.shaunsalzberg.com/medialab/foodgroups_v1\nhttp://www.shaunsalzberg.com/medialab/powerflowers\nhttp://www.shaunsalzberg.com/medialab/point_and_shoot_data','','','Hi New Lab, I\'m Shaun Salzberg, a recent MIT Media Lab grad and current Design Technologist at digital design firm Control Group. Professionally, I\'m a software engineer with a specialty in web and mobile development, but personally I\'m a designer, inventor, and entrepreneur with a 10-page list of both hardware and software ideas just itching to be built.  I\'m currently looking to make the leap to the freelance world as I continue to work on prototyping one of my more promising product ideas and building up a company around it. I\'m therefore on the search for studio space / shop space in the NYC area, and I\'d love to learn more about New Lab and visit the space. \n\nThanks! Please feel free to contact me at 732-718-9617 or shaun.salzberg@gmail.com to discuss further.\n\n- Shaun\n\nIn case you\'re interested, some current and past projects I\'ve worked on include:\nhttp://www.transitory.me/\nhttp://www.substringthegame.com/\nhttp://www.shaunsalzberg.com/medialab/fabclass/final\nhttp://www.shaunsalzberg.com/medialab/quarkz\nhttp://www.shaunsalzberg.com/medialab/periodic_table\nhttp://www.shaunsalzberg.com/medialab/foodgroups_v1\nhttp://www.shaunsalzberg.com/medialab/powerflowers\nhttp://www.shaunsalzberg.com/medialab/point_and_shoot_data','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:07','2016-03-26 00:06:07'),(488,'0015-06-23','Lars','Molkentin','info@gps-makler.de','','www.gps-makler.de','','','','Transportation','','sales Telematik and Gps','','','Please Senf me news','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:07','2016-03-26 00:06:07'),(489,'0015-06-23','Jordan','Mayerson','jordan@hoplitepower.com','','www.hoplitepower.com','','','','Connected Hardware','','At Hoplite Power, we understand the importance of staying connected. Whether it’s to meet up with a friend around the block or video chat with a loved one across the world, your smartphone is there for you—except when it’s not. When your battery dies, so do those connections. Have you ever tried to surf the web or download a new app on a dead phone? No? Yea, doesn’t work for us either.  We\'re here to defend your mobile usage habits by providing smartphone charging that keeps up with the pace of you, making battery power an afterthought\n\nCurrently expanding in NYC, our “charge-sharing” network consists of a squadron of Hoplite Hubs located in various businesses all around the city. These proprietary, small-footprint Hoplite Hubs store, dispense, and automatically recharge Hoplites, which are ergonomically-designed, universal battery packs that can be rented from and returned to any Hub in the network. With Hoplite Power, you can easily charge your smartphone on the go—no wires or outlets required! We keep your power protected so you always stay connected. \n\nWe have put together an extremely talented team of engineers, entrepreneurs and advisors who are working in tandem to get our product off the ground and running.','','','We are currently developing our product out of Artisan Asylum in Boston as nothing like it exists in NYC until New Lab was created; hence, we are extremely extremely interested in the space as we see it as a great opportunity to have our development under the same roof as the rest of the business. Following our prototyping process, we would look to move to New Lab from our current co-working space in the Lower East Side (note that our development is in Boston but the rest of the team is in NYC).\n\nPlease note that our current website is about to be replaced a much more responsive and information-filled website at the end of the month. I would love to learn as much about New Lab as possible and would love to be able to tour the space since it looks absolutely amazing. This will be a great addition to the NYC creative/design/engineering/entrepreneurial world and my team and I would love to be a part of the first generation of New Lab members.','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:07','2016-03-26 00:06:07'),(490,'0015-06-23','Maurice','Bey','3dfabnow@gmail.com','','Non','','','','Additive Technology','','3Dprinting of homes','','','I want to know about the cost of membership for space to work in.\nThank you','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:07','2016-03-26 00:06:07'),(491,'0015-06-01','Joel','Murphy','biomurph@gmail.com','','www.openbci.com  www.pulsesensor.com','','','','Medical','','I design open source hardware. \nI am  co-founder of three tech startups in Brooklyn:\nWorld Famous Electronics, makers of Pulse Sensor, an optical heart rate monitor for Arduino. Pulse Sensor was Kickstarted in 2011 http://kck.st/1EQkiwv as a development tool for makers who want to use heartbeats into their projects. The Pulse Sensor Kit is sold on our website, as well as  on Adafruit and Sparkfun, and many other online resellers of Open Source hardware. \nOpenBCI, a high-quality, low-cost, EEG system for researchers, scientists, developers, and hackers.  OpenBCI was born of my involvement in an SBIR grant that I and my partner leveraged into a Kickstarter that was funded in 2014 http://kck.st/1K5wG2C. OpenBCI is disrupting the field of non-invasive brain research by providing a low cost, mobile, medical grade EEG system that is completely customizable. We sell our system to scientists, engineers, researchers,  developers, and biofeedback enthusiasts. We are a very young company, but we have big goals. We are currently working on the a 3D printed electrode headset for EEG that is customizable to our user\'s exact head size and shape. Also, we are working on an even lower-cost biosignal acquisition system that  will target the DIY and Maker market.\nI also have a small consulting firm, called Solutions Design & Prototyping that solves problems and prototypes solutions for artists, designers, and inventors.\nMy background is in the arts. I have a BFA from Mass Art in Boston, and an MFA from UC San Diego,  I taught Physical Computing at Parsons, the New School for Design from 2006 to 2014. I am a self-taught design engineer.\nI am not done. I have a couple more ideas that I plan to launch in the coming  months, and I am very interested in a supportive environment to base them in.\nCheers! Joel','','','I am currently working in the old Pfizer building, and our lease is coming due in August. I would like to transition to a new space that has more of a technology focus (Pfizer is mostly industrial kitchens). I will be brining with me my partner in OpenBCI, along with our tools and equipment, as well as another partner that I work with in my consulting business I would like to know:\nHow big are the spaces you are offering?\nWhat is the rate?\nWhat kind of power are you providing for tenants? (voltage and current, not political)\nIs there freight/loading dock access?\nI have some tools (mill, wood tools) do you have restrictions on tooling in the studio spaces?\nWhen do you expect the move-in date? \n\nLooks like a super place!\nBest,\nJoel','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:07','2016-03-26 00:06:07'),(492,'0015-05-24','Deren','Guler','deren@invent-abling.com','','www.teknikio.com','','','','Education','','Teknikio designs and creates toolsets that teach you how to embed technology into any object through craft and design. We are a small team of 2 to 4 (depending on the project) and collaborate with others on a contract basis. Though focused on education and primarily attracting girls to STEM fields, we work to make our products gender neutral, and accessible to anyone.  Each set is designed to show you how to merge a craft such as paper folding, sewing, or basic prototyping with a foundational concept in science or engineering. We regularly work with schools, museums, and other organizations, locally and internationally, to teach workshops and create custom toolsets. Deren just finished her fellowship at the New York Hall of Science as the inaugural Design Fellow, where she worked with museum staff to develop content and interactive projects relating to her research. \nWe currently have space in a Fab Lab which has provided a wonderful community and are looking to move into a space with a similar atmosphere. Unfortunately we have outgrown our current location and need to find a new studio as soon as possible. We visited the New Lab over a year ago and have been hoping to join the community in some way ever since. The facilities and community of the New Lab are very exciting and inspiring to us and we believe it would provide the perfect ecosystem for us to grow. We would also love to collaborate with any of the existing tenants if they are interested in developing an educational kit around their work and have the skills and experience to help develop and test new concepts for educational and hobby-centric toolsets.  Additionally, we have experience with manufacturing and would be interested in sharing resources and finding new ways to streamline our processes.','','','I would be interested in the fabrication tools that are available to members and the costs for using them.  \nI would also be interested in the degree of community within the space- are members encouraged to meet with each other, are there any events that focus on building collaboration? Some other spaces I have looked at have various degrees of this in place. We would love to be a part of this community and believe that it would foster a lot of new creativity in and and around our projects.','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:07','2016-03-26 00:06:07'),(493,'0015-05-22','Howard','Chambers','howard@chambersprojects.me','','www.citysoftwalks.com','','','','Built Environments','','I am committed to the belief that major urban metropolises should be designed with people as the primary user. I am driven by the realization that despite this ideal—cars, construction and infrastructure have taken precedence over human needs.I believe in the necessity of bringing educational opportunities and psychological respites into unconsidered interstitial spaces. Modular components, user-generated design, creative programming and multi-use sites are all a part of my design approach. \nA graduate from the Transdisciplinary Design MFA program at Parsons the New School for Design, I focused on rethinking and re-imagining outdated infrastructure throughout New York City for the past few years. My interdisciplinary approach includes connecting urban development while preserving artistic culture and unique sense of place by creating a team dynamic that fuses individuals of different disciplines. She focused on making connections between the city’s D.O.T., developers, business improvement districts, architects, city planners, lighting designers, urban designers, and event coordinators to help evaluate archaic systems and define experimental projects that yield necessary and measurable results.','','','I am interesting in joining the Real Lab so that I can meet like-minded people who are makers,  hold vast amounts of curiosity and are entrepreneurs at heart. Living in Dumbo, the Navy Yard is very close and I have always wanted to be connected to this area since moving to NYC from SF in 2010. I am looking for help to prototype ideas, collaborate on projects and for a space to facilitate my workshops which give city planners, architect firms, and  developers have hands-on experience of adopting a design thinking approach to their process.','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:07','2016-03-26 00:06:07'),(494,'0015-05-17','Kamil','Nawratil','info@volvoxlabs.com','','www.volvoxlabs.com','','','','Other','','Hello! \n\nWe are VolvoxLabs [aka, VVOX] . We are a  boutique, new media design studio working at the intersection of the digital and physical, to foster new opportunities from emerging technologies. Using the latest software and rendering processes, we explore new possibilities in form, structure, composition, and performance. From anamorphic creatures to cellular realization and vast cyber spaces, our 3D/2D visual skills create abstract universe and worlds. Together we use our visual skills to transform public space into interactive art and community engagement. Through a combination of audiovisual performance, interactive architectural installation and 3D animation, we make a space--an experience. From ideation to  fabrication, we develop our work every step of the way.\n\nWe are led by Co-Founder and Creative Director, Kamil Nawratil, a Polish-born visual artist based in Brooklyn, New York. His work examines the struggle, breakdown and eventual evolution of systems; and explores relationships within visual, tactile, motion, and sound perception. He received his MFA in Computer Art from the School of Visual Arts, at which time he also founded Volvox Labs; a new-media and visual design studio\n\nVVOX\'s Co-founder Pa Her is a psychologist with the unique position of also being a interdisciplinary researcher and creative tinker. She serves as the managing partner at VVOX. Using applied behavioral research and psychological insights to drive emotionally driven experiences, she  is the critical eye between the designers and the client. She received her PhD from Virginia Tech in 2008 and is currently Assistant Professor at the City University of New York at City Tech teaching psychology to technology and design students.','','','Hello New Lab,\n\nWe are interested in New Lab to forge more interdisciplinary collaborations and protoype  new media projects.  Our work is a synergy of new media technologies, traditional architecture, computer art and psychology. We\'d love  to partner with other companies to create products that otherwise would be impossible to achieve.  We truly believe the whole is greater than the sum of its parts—like a Volvox!  We do our best work when we are working with a group of linked minded artists/technologists, and New Lab is the place where we want to cultivate our ideas! We imagine the lab will be a technological and creative resource, as well as the seed for new creative collaborations  and innovations.  \n\n We look forward to hearing you soon. Can\'t wait to see the finished building!','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:07','2016-03-26 00:06:07'),(495,'0015-05-11','Matthew','Flego','Matt@mattanderikdesign.com','','www.mattanderikdesign.com','','','','Other','','Erik and I are a design and invention company that seeks to help inventors and businesses concerned with sustainable focused work.','','','We are curious about any residency programs available and studio space.  We thrive in the makerspace environment. \n\nhttp://www.uvm.edu/~uvmpr/?Page=news&storyID=20843&category=four_sq','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:08','2016-03-26 00:06:08'),(496,'0015-05-06','William','Norskog','wnorskog@gmail.com','','www.norskog.co','','','','Industrial Design','','Greetings! I\'m a skilled craftsmen, who works primarily with metal. Here\'s a link with some of my more recent works: \n\nhttps://drive.google.com/open?id=0B0QwqP7VSRpCb2M1cVlaUHdZNlE&authuser=0','','','I\'m unclear whether this is just some new age co-working space or if you could employ a full time talented fabricator? If the latter please let me know, thanks!','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:08','2016-03-26 00:06:08'),(497,'0015-05-05','Jonathan','Stidd','jonathanstidd@gmail.com','','http://www.faucetfriend.us/','','','','Consumer Products','','Faucet Friend is a patent pending device that allows any sink to be retrofitted into an automatic faucet in under 10 minutes. Benefits:\nEnvironmental - decreasing water consumption nearly up to 70%\nPersonal - saves money in utilities and decreases spread of germs\n\nI would like to work with New Lab to build a professional prototype for this product, beyond what is demonstrated on the website.','','','Looking forward to hearing from you.  Thank you for your time!','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:08','2016-03-26 00:06:08'),(498,'0015-04-26','Jeff','Crouse','jeff@odddivision.com','','https://twitter.com/odddivision','','','','Other','','We make interactive installations for institutions and brands using technology and design.','','','We are a new company (2 years) currently based at NEW INC, but need more space to prototype and build. We would love to learn more about New Lab and if it would be a good fit for us.','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:08','2016-03-26 00:06:08'),(499,'0015-04-23','Jacob','Russo','russo.jacob7@gmail.com','','drift-arch.com','','','','Built Environments','','I graduated from the Carnegie Mellon University School of Architecture with a B. Arch in 2014 and am currently a junior architect working in New York City. I have a strong interest in urban agriculture, green infrastructure, and biomimicry in conjunction with computation and digital fabrication. I strive to collaborate on compelling, innovative design projects related to energy, food, and water systems, as well as storm preparedness and resiliency. For my undergraduate thesis, \"Locavoracious,\" I researched urban agriculture and aquaponics to propose a new paradigm for \"live-grow\" building envelopes in Stuyvesant Town, NYC. \nI am an avid model builder and having worked as a monitor and TA at the CMU SoArch wood shop for 3 years, I am confident in the creative use and teaching as well as the technical maintenance and repair of shop equipment. In addition, I participated in a number of courses and an advanced design studio, which focussed on the application of an array of machinery in CMU’s extensive digital fabrication lab. I have proficient knowledge of laser cutters, 3D printers and CNC mills and also have experience with 6-axis robots in conjunction with industry standard Mastercam software for advanced CNC toolpathing and RobotStudio for ABB robotics. I love to make and prototype at various scales in support of the concepts and projects I mentioned above and hope to continue to find the resources to bring unique visions to life.','','','Born and raised in Manhattan, and having travelled to some of the world\'s other major cities, such as Milan and Tokyo, I have come to appreciate the symbiotic relationship between people and the built environment and how important it is to balance all the networks and flows in and around the urban realm. I chose the name \"Drift\" for my website to emphasize my focus on these flows and to exemplify the idea of the continual evolution of both the issues I try to tackle as well as my design process itself. The notion of transformation relates strongly to the discipline of architecture as well. In recent years, advances in digital technology, materials science, and biology have revolutionized the construction industry. I believe the intersection of multiple disciplines and technologies in well-conceived, collaborative spaces has the potential to radically transform the way we think about design, education, and how we shape our surroundings. I would like to be a part of this evolution and believe I have both the experience and skills to not only thrive in a place like the New Lab, but to bring people together to make a substantial impact across many fields.','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:08','2016-03-26 00:06:08'),(500,'0015-04-23','Cris','Grether','','','coca-cola.com','','','','Consumer Products','','Design Capabilities','','','Just curious to learn about hosting a co- creation meeting there. Fees? Etc','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:08','2016-03-26 00:06:08'),(501,'0015-04-22','Larry','Rosenthal','','','www.cube3.com','','','','Industrial Design','','I was one of the earliest designers and artists in NYC to work in  3D RT CGI , Virtual Reality, AR, transmedia and even 3D printing. I still work at the bleeding edge of where all 3D RT media comes together','','','Hi. My bio can be read by this current  interview  at UploadVR magazine .  Id love to get involved.\nhttp://uploadvr.com/flashback-larry-rosenthal/','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:08','2016-03-26 00:06:08'),(502,'0015-04-22','Arthur','Sebert','','','www.my3dmatter.com','','','','Additive Technology','','My startup, 3D Matter, is a 3D printing materials specialist. We test third-party materials to establish standards in the industry and we formulate new chemistries to develop innovative consumables. \n\nDue to today’s market structure, there are only a few, expensive materials available for current applications. By developing an expertise focused on 3D printing materials, 3D Matter hopes to improve the value chain and bring 3D printer users closer to materials while leaving hardware and software matters to printer manufacturers.\n\nWe have got some traction from the initial studies we published on our website, and we got press from key 3D printing websites, such as:\n\nhttp://3dprintingindustry.com/2015/01/21/pla-best-3d-printing-ask-3d-matter/\nhttp://www.3ders.org/articles/20150311-optimize-the-quality-of-your-3d-prints-through-this-handy-study.html','','','We are looking for an office space with more room than the typical incubator space. We need space for our 3D printers, testing machines, and we potentially also need formulation capabilities (mixing chemicals, extruding filament etc.), so our requirements go beyond the basic office space.\n\nWe believe the New Lab may be a great solution for us and would like to get in touch with you to better understand your offering. Would you have some time to discuss with us?\n\nBest,\nArthur','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:08','2016-03-26 00:06:08'),(503,'0015-04-21','Alex Miles','Younger','','','http://alexmilesyounger.com','','','','Education','','Working on projects related to publishing, media, education, wearables, and behavior change.','','','Hi, \n\nLooking forward to seeing what New Lab becomes. I want access to the people and tools that will help shape the most interesting projects of the next decade and I think that\'s here.','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:08','2016-03-26 00:06:08'),(504,'0015-04-11','Zachary','Jones','','','www.projectwosho.com','','','','Other','','It’s like Tesla Motors, but for houses. Project Wosho is looking to prove that the current home designs and manufacturing methods are outdated and inferior to the technologies that are available. To achieve this, we design and build homes using new technologies like Structural Insulated Panels, 12 volt DC automated electrical systems, bioclimatic architectural design, and a bit of influence from the space efficient designs brought to us by the tiny house movement. Our house designs right now mostly fall under the category of tiny houses. In the future we plan to expand our product to larger homes and introduce new innovations along the way. \n\nThere is potential for our homes to reduce and manage water and energy consumption, minimize carbon footprint, have electronic integration, home automation, and lower total costs, all without compromising comfort or beauty. With each generation of our homes produced, we will increase the affordability by developing advanced manufacturing techniques.','','','Hi New Lab!  We came across your article on entrepreneur.com and immediately knew that we needed to get in contact. My co-founder and I are working on setting the stage for the emerging housing market shift and have been bootstraping our startup since 2011.  Starting a home manufacturing company is very different from your usual tech startup. We have applied to a handful of big name incubators. These incubators  have told us they really like what we are doing but don\'t see a way they could benefit us due to us not being a true tech startup. It\'s very seldom that we run into a group so well versed and in line with our vision as a company. It\'s very exciting to us to read about your mission, your team, and your tenants on the website . We would love to chat with you guys and learn more about New Lab, what you do,  and how we could fit in to your program. \n\nFor us there is a sense of urgency in growing our company.  We have seen companies similar to ours lose traction despite having great  products. Our traction has been outstanding and we know that there is only so much that a two man team can handle. Currently we have over 150 order forms filled out and will be building our prototype for a paying customer this year. Once we build this home we expect a spike in interest and we want to be prepared for it. We think New Lab might be that key component to propel us. \n\nWe are looking forward to hearing back from you! \n\nZack Jones\nCo-founder of Project Wosho\n(434) 685-1045','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:08','2016-03-26 00:06:08'),(505,'0015-04-07','Scott','Winslow','','','https://scott-winslow.squarespace.com','','','','Industrial Design','','I am an designer, maker and creative director. Most recently I was the creative director for Harvard professor David Edwards at his idea-incubation lab in Paris, Le Laboratoire. Le Lab exists as a pure whitespace innovation hub across cultural, educational and commercial ventures. In my work with Dr. Edwards we developed such crazy sounding things as breathable foods and edible packaging--both concepts made it out of the Lab and into the marketplace in the US an EU.\n\nIn my many pursuits I have designed and fabricated everything from wooden boats, blown glass, ceramics, metals, custom lighting installation, digital UX, retail environments and more.\n\nI have recently formed a consultancy and work across product design (high-end lighting, home accessories), brand identity/packaging and environment design. \n\nMy work is inspired by a meshing of  mathematical forms such as computational origami, with biological forms found in nature.','','','Fantastic project, BRAVO! I would love to be immersed in this amazing space with like-minded entrepreneurs and forward thinking designers.','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:08','2016-03-26 00:06:08'),(506,'0015-04-01','Rita','Bermudez Esquerra','','','http://www.hp.com','','','','Additive Technology','','HP is a leader product, software, technology and solutions provider. Recently announced Blended Reality Ecosystem to open up new market categories that will define the future, empowering people to create, interact and inspire like never before. Blended reality is a way to blend the digital world with the physical world we live in. Blended reality is more than an idea, it\'s a vision. A promise. And with it, we\'re re imagining a whole new world of possibilities. With 3D Printing on the horizon, experience how HP will enable ideas to take shape, literally transforming digital expressions into the physical, completing the vision of blended reality. A vision that ultimately will reinvent the innovation process and transform how industries design and manufacture. A vision powered by HPs Multi Jet Fusion TM technology and accelerated via a unique open platform approach, which calls on industry software and materials partners to collaborate with HP in advancing the state-of-the-art of 3D printing.','','','Hello team, this is Rita Bermúdez, HP 3D Printing Business Events Manager. based in Barcelona, Spain. Taking into account I will be landing NY next April 14th to assist at the Keynote our Director is going to present at Inside 3D Print Event on Thursday 16th I will appreciate if we can setup some time on April 15th to visit your facilities, know about your project,  the team behind the project, membership opportunities and last but not least evaluate your facility as a potential place for future HP Events related with 3D Printing. Let me know if someone from your team could contact me to close on a time that best suits during April 15th. \nThanks a lot!! Keep in touch, \nRita. ','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:08','2016-03-26 00:06:08'),(507,'0015-03-23','Eric','Danziger','','','www.invisible.ai','','','','Robotics','','Currently a graduate student at CMU studying robotics. \n\nLooking to start a company this summer.','','','I am interested in New Lab, and would at like to visit sometime this summer. My group still lives in Pittsburgh, but are interested in moving to New York post graduation in December of this year.','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:08','2016-03-26 00:06:08'),(508,'0015-03-19','Shaun','Arora','','','www.makeinla.com','','','','Other','','Creating a maker space in LA initially as coworking and eventually as  an accelerator.','','','Hoping to see Scott and New Lab Thursday morning March 26, while I\'m in NYC.  Erik from LACI recommended I reach out.','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:08','2016-03-26 00:06:08'),(509,'0015-03-06','Annelie','Berner','','','www.annelieberner.com','','','','Connected Hardware','','I am a data artist, designer and technologist. I\'m interested in how we understand, think about, and interact with our digital worlds, especially as these relate to how we compartmentalize information across objects and devices. My work is concerned with aesthetics, tangible representations of data. I design, develop and prototype both digital and physical representations of data.\n\nI\'m currently a member of NEWINC, the arts-tech incubator of the New Museum, where I am developing \"AiryLight\" - a kinetic light that visualizes realtime air quality data, among other projects. \nI teach Experimental Interaction Design at Rutgers College of Art & Design and am responsible for a variety of data visualization projects for a range of clients - from news organizations to start ups. Meanwhile, I continue to develop various iterations of \"AiryLight\" - both for installations and for individuals. It is currently headed to the Georgia Museum of Art for an exhibition on Big Data.\n\nMy work will also be exhibited at the New York Hall of Science (upcoming exhibit: Art of Networks) and I was a recipient of a Core77 Design Award for my project “Cupcakes Index.” Other projects have been featured in Dwell, Make Magazine and Visualising Data. \n\nPrior to joining NEWINC, I worked as an Associate Research Scholar at the Spatial Information Design Lab and Adjunct Assistant Professor at Columbia University\'s School of Architecture. I studied Government and Visual and Environmental Studies at Harvard and am a recent graduate of New York University’s Interactive Telecommunications Program (ITP).','','','I am excited about New Lab in that it seems to bring together a very exciting cross section of skills and disciplines. In my own work, I combine physical and digital fabrication with data-sensing or internet-enabled hardware. \nWhile some of my client work is purely digital, some of my clients are artists who seek to collaborate and make large-scale physical installations using new fabrication methods. It would be fantastic to have access to the woodworking shop and digital fabrication shop.\nI would very much like to be considered to be a member at New Lab and would love to talk about the possibility of adding to the community free events such as quick workshops or skillshares, if this were appropriate.','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:08','2016-03-26 00:06:08'),(510,'0015-03-04','Madison','Maxey','','','www.thecrated.com','','','','Consumer Products','','We do collaborative product development in the wearable technology and enhanced apparel space. Current portfolio projects in which we\'ve invested product development  include a hydrophobic menswear brand, a photochromic clothing line and a module for Little bits that senses gesture. \n\nPress features include Fast Company, PSFK and Wearable news. We\'re excited to be developing IP around the wearable technology space in the upcoming months!','','','I would love to learn more about being part of New Inc.','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:08','2016-03-26 00:06:08'),(511,'0015-03-02','Rich','Watts','','','http://richwatts.com','','','','Other','','I\'m a designer-developer-entrepreneur-fabricator-engineer-artist and driven in no small part by a desire to add more hyphens to this list.\n\nI\'m a co-founder of Trade School: a non-traditional learning space that runs on barter, OurGoods: an online bartering network for creatives, Industry City Distillery: a non-traditional distillery in Brooklyn and Super A-OK: a creative agency currently developing a three-dimensional camera system. \n\nI\'ve been in NY for the last 10 years and have a machine shop and studio in Sunset Park Brooklyn.','','','I\'ve followed the development of New Lab for quite some time and would like to learn more about the spaces and resources you\'ll be offering once open. I\'ve had some experience with Autodesk\'s Pier 9 space/project and really like the similar direction New Lab seems to be heading here in NY.','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:08','2016-03-26 00:06:08'),(512,'0015-02-10','Geo','Salas','','','www.geovannysalas.com','','','','Industrial Design','','Recently I have been Certified in 3D Printing and currently enrolled in the Digital Fabrication Certificate Program for Subtractive Fabrication Processes: Laser Cutting/CNC Milling at New York City College of Technology, where I obtained modeling/computational skills to create water-tight designs and produce a number of types of 3D prints. Projects that provided experience in the use of a variety of tools, equipment, concepts, and emerging digitally-driven technologies, including parametric rule-based design, finishing and assembly techniques, and iterative design processes. I have also studied Toy Design at the Fashion Institute of Technology, where I learned the design and invention process, as well as effective ways to visually communicate concepts for toy products. In the duration of the course we brainstormed, created sketches, idea books and presentation boards. I also have experience in production, specifically in the Art Department for several television and commercials shoots. I worked closely with Prop Stylists, Set Designers and Culinary Producers in mostly maintaining the brand integrity for clients.','','','.','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:08','2016-03-26 00:06:08'),(513,'0015-02-06','Jeremiah','Miller','','','www.smartergridsolutions.com','','','','Energy','','Automation controls company that increases the hosting capacity of existing electric grids for clean energy by 200%-300%. We are a U.K. company that is bringing this technology to North America, and we are growing to big for our NYU-Poly/ACRE home and need a larger space.','','','Hi - we are interested in a 1000sf up to 5000sf space. A private/secure but flexible space we can grow from.  If you will have any space by spring 2015, please contact me. Best - Jeremiah','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:08','2016-03-26 00:06:08'),(514,'0015-01-31','Rebeccah','Pailes-Friedman','','','http://getinterwoven.com/','','','','Industrial Design','','Multidisciplinary research and design practice  that spacializes in smart textiles and wearable technology.','','','I am currently research fellow at Pratt\'s BF+ DA and director of Pratt\'s IMARI Lab as well as a faculty member in ID and Fashion. My private practice, RPF Industrial Design  is growing and we are launching a rebranding this coming spring. Soon we will be Interwoven Design. I am looking for a home for my business where we can share our ideas and join a community of like minded people. New Lab sounds like home.','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:08','2016-03-26 00:06:08'),(515,'0015-01-26','Joseph','Weissgold','','','thefutureproject.org','','','','Education','','The Future Project is an education non-profit working in High Schools across the country. Our Dream Directors work as full time staff in those schools, guiding young people to identify their passions and purpose and transform them into Future Projects. In our four years since starting, we\'ve expanded to over 30 schools in 7 cities. As we continue to grow, we\'re finding the increasing need for access to fabrication tools, both for prototyping in the development of new products to support our Dream Directors who work in the field, and for supporting young people\'s Future Projects as they hope to literally make their dreams real.','','','My name\'s Joseph. I am the Principal Designer and Director of Insights at The Future Project. One aspect of my role is the development of new products, but our current office is missing some of the basic necessities of prototyping. \n\nMy background is Industrial Design, and after having worked at a few design firms and studied at schools including Parsons and SVA, I\'ve become accustomed to having a wide array of fabrication tools around me, digital and not. My team appreciates the need for access to these tools, so I\'m currently in the market for a membership to a co-working maker space.\n\nPlease, if you can, let me know what becoming a member entails and what access to resources it offers.','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:08','2016-03-26 00:06:08'),(516,'0015-01-22','Neil','Wiita','','','neilwiita.com','','','','Industrial Design','','The physical manifestation of my design work is on multiple scales, from consumer products to furniture to installations to architecture. I have a masters in architecture, but find the practice to be stagnant in NYC and hope to break out of the industry and work towards several smaller scale design projects. I have recently left a full-time position at Kliment Halsband Architects and am currently freelancing as a parametric design consultant for Coach in Manhattan, developing a methodology to go from flat pattern to an automated 3d modeled representation and back through grasshopper and scripting.  I am also in the process of bringing various product design projects to market, but all of them require rapid prototyping capabilities that I don\'t have.    My individual design work is focused on technology intersecting with materiality, and through architecture school I have had experience with and machine time on laser cutters, 3D printers, and CNC machines for 12 years.  Also a few years ago I became fascinated with sensor networks and their ability to be linked to kinetic design objects.  This has brought me into the world of arduino, and linking the physical sensors with the digital manifestation in grasshopper through firefly. The other side of my design work is focused on acoustics, as I have been experimenting with speaker design as well as tube amp design and manufacture for the past 8 years. My graduate thesis focused primarily on sound and the built environment, making an acoustically transformative urban soundscape that reacts in response to environmental sounds.','','','I am very interested in a small studio space (500 sq.ft. max) and machine access. I have been waiting for a viable fab lab to open up in Brooklyn, and would love to be involved.\n\n I am very interested to know the rental rate / shop fees / what actual equipment (shop and digital fabrication) will be available as well as what sort of ventilation/light is available in the studio spaces.\n\nAlso I may be interested in co-working space as opposed to individual studio space depending on the pricing, and would appreciate any information that you can provide on the layout/setup of the co-working space and if there would be storage opportunities.\n\nThanks, Neil Wiita','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:08','2016-03-26 00:06:08'),(517,'0015-01-22','Rebeccah','Pailes-Friedman','','','http://getinterwoven.com/','','','','Industrial Design','','Industrial design  firm specializing in wearable technology and smart textiles','','','My multidisciplinary wearable technology design firm needs a home among piers. Our clients are primarily funded startups in health, personal safety and athletic next tux market segments. I would like to speak with you about joining new lab when it opens.','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:08','2016-03-26 00:06:08'),(518,'0015-01-18','Jerry','Staub','','','none','','','','Consumer Products','','Hello, I\'m Jerry Staub. I\'d be interested in better understanding what resources will be available as I am aiming to develop a physical product to bring to B2B and B2C markets, but lack a design / engineering background.','','','Will there be incubator services / guidance available or is this mostly a work space that is available?','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:08','2016-03-26 00:06:08'),(519,'0015-01-09','Mara','Haseltine','','','calamara@mac.com','','','','Other','','The practice ‘Geotherapy’* informs all of my work. Geotherapy embraces the future by addressing the link between our cultural and biological evolution.  I am a multi-disciplinary science based green product designer, installation artist, and educator combining advanced digital technology, bioinformatics product design and art.  In addition, I am an ardent environmentalist and have been putting together cross disciplinary think tanks for the past ten years which introduce technologists for environmental solutions to NGO’s, investors and governmental organizations. \n\nI am currently producing three bodies of work which all address the concept of ‘Geotherapy’ on a material level.  The first body of work is a green product line utilizing recycled materials and transforming them into objects for citywide use which will both functional and beautiful. The second body of work is restorative comprised of structures for living aquatic life which does not use plastic or concrete created to be reabsorbed by the environment they are biodegradable, non-toxic, act as bio-remediation filters, create habitat, and provide coastline protection. The third body of work is art-awareness installations which translate microscopic data from bioinformatics into large-scale figurative forms often using computer generated milling.  This body of work depicts the human impact on our delicate microscopic world.  These awareness works sequester toxins like plastic and uranium infused glass, and are meant for museums, galleries and public institutions. The final intention of all my work is to create awareness of the beneficial impact of ‘Geotherapy’ on our planet.\n\n*Note: The word ‘Geotherapy’ was coined by a panel of scientists at the Universite Claude Bernard in 1991 lead by Dr. Richard Grantham and Dr. Van Rensselaer Potter in Lyon, France to address the need to establish a global bioethic in the face of human induced climate change.  link to original ‘Geotherapy Declaration’: http://www.calamara.com/geotherapy-declaration/','','','I have always been drawn to the rich community of creative thinkers and the amazing array of businesses that the Navy Yard offers.  I was first introduced to the newlab by Mitch Joachim of TerraForm One when I visited his newlab beta last year. I was enthralled when he showed me the future facility site next to the water and described its multi-use resources and the incredible group of future tenants already gathered. Upon learning that newlab is visionary David Belt ‘Macro-sea’ brain child the entire project made perfect sense to me as I have been following David’s inspiring work since “Glassphamy” in 2010.  I am particularly drawn to the emphasis that the new lab puts on environmental solutions and future thinking.\n\nI see myself participating in the new lab community on multiple levels.  As a designer and artist I would like to rent a studio space within the new lab for my small business.  I would utilize the shared equipment to design my green prototype designs make art for large scale public art projects as well fine art.\n\nI am very interested in the cultural aspect of the space and how such an incubator could better serve the community at large.  To this end I would like to use the communal space as an educator to conduct workshops, classes and help formulate a lecture series with the other members of new lab.   It would also be an ideal place to showcase green innovation and to continue my work creating cross-over green think tanks.  To tell you the honest truth once I found out about the creation of the new lab there is no where in New York City I would rather become a working part of.','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:08','2016-03-26 00:06:08'),(520,'0015-01-01','Nora','Ligorano','','','Http://ligoranoreese.net','','','','Other','','We are a collaborative team, Nora Ligorano and Marshall Reese, and have been tenants in BNY building 30 for the past 11 years.  We are the co-founders of the  only  building in the Navy Yard fully occupied by artists., established in 2003.\n\nWe make public art works as well as limited edition sculptural works and unique pieces that  address issues and trends in our culture.  From political , social , ecological and cultural topics, our work has  had broad exposure and is represented by Catherine Clark Gallery.\n\nWe will look forward to meeting you in the future, and look forward to the  completion of  your renovation. (The building is looking great!)','','','We are interest  in connecting with  your new community of designers and companies  that  intersect art and technology .  \n\nWe are also interested in the  the workshop environment, with access to / or working with technicians to realize projects  using 3 d printers and laser cutters .','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:08','2016-03-26 00:06:08'),(521,'0014-12-28','Jia','Li','','','jiacollection.com','','','','Consumer Products','','Multifunctional fashion lifestyle brand.','','','I would love to be updated with your progress and the possibility of renting the studio space when available. I am always on the look out for innovative material and applications that I can apply to fashion or fashion-related products.','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:08','2016-03-26 00:06:08'),(522,'0014-12-24','Anthony','McCann','','','www.Forkologist.com','','','','Consumer Products','','Silversmith 18 years specialist in flatware to jewelry production.','','','What are the qualifications for selection and who are the judges, there qualifications and are there recommendations final ?','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:08','2016-03-26 00:06:08'),(523,'0014-12-22','Benji Rogers','Benji Rogers','','','www.pledgemusic.com','','','','Other','','Founder and President','','','I live close by in Dumbo! Excited to learn more.\nThx\nB','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:08','2016-03-26 00:06:08'),(524,'0014-12-22','Jesse','Simpson','','','www.jessesimpson.com/cymbals','','','','Other','','I make custom cymbals in the old style, completely by hand. I start from a flat piece of bronze and work it into a cymbal shape, then lathe the cymbal to its final specification. I also modify preexisting cymbals for percussionists based on what they need it to sound like.','','','I\'d love to be a part of New Lab and offer my skills as part of the community! What I do is very different from 3d printing and mass manufacturing but I find a great deal of value in it. I noticed this more when I exhibited my work at Maker Faire NY and got a lot of attention for reverse engineering a lost craft rather than working on something completely new.','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:08','2016-03-26 00:06:08'),(525,'0014-12-08','Jochen','Hartmann','','','jochenhartmann.com','','','','Built Environments','','I am currently a member of the New Inc as one of eight alums from GSAPP (Columbia University graduate school of Architecture) who were offered free desks there. I am working as the project lead for \'The Synapse\', a large scale architectural installation  to be placed in the Jerome L Greene science center currently being built uptown with the mandate of making neuroscience accessible to a wide audience through visualizations, robotics, gaming and education  (http://spatialinformationdesignlab.org/projects/synapse). I am also an artist (graduate from RISD) and a game designer (both digital and analog), with a few titles in print such as  Cave Evil, an acclaimed underground dungeon brawl (http://www.cave-evil.com/) and Symtactics, a game developed for the Uneven Growth exhibit currently at the MoMA.','','','Hi,\n\nI am interested in memberships for 2015. My apartment is literally only a few blocks away so this would be an ideal work space for me. Please keep me posted\n\nThanks\n- J','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:08','2016-03-26 00:06:08'),(526,'0014-12-04','Jon','Eicher','','','www.joneicher.com   www.specializedcomposites.com','','','','Industrial Design','','I have an extensive history in Brooklyn having started a fine art, design, fabrication studio in Dumbo in 1993 after graduating from the School of Visual Arts MFA Fine Arts program.  In that time I worked for a variety of leading companies and artists in design, fabrication, fine art, etc.  One of the most interesting jobs was working for New York Aquarium in their fiberglass shop. More of a laboratory than a production shop I got to learn how to use composites which at the time was almost a \"black art\" as information about composite fabrication was almost impossible to find.  After leaving there I continued to study and make things from composites.  Eventually I moved into the realm of \"advanced composites\" like carbon fiber, Kevlar, and hybrid materials and their unique manufacturing processes.\n\nCurrently,  I am solely focused on building a design / fabrication /manufacturing, entrepreneurial business around the use of carbon fiber and these other advanced materials.  The processes I use are very clean, environmentally friendly, and state of the art in material science.  I am making the future now. \n\nI would like to find a space that has like minded individuals.  It would also be great to have access to CAD/ CAM software and tools, 3D printers, multi axis machines, etc., that are beyond the finances of a start up or small business. \n\nI have customers all over the world and have shipped finished products to over 40 counties.','','','What I do is friendly to a group environment. Does not smell or generate large amounts of dust.  I currently work in a scale of about 4\' x 8\' maximum. What I do is design/engineer and fabricate my products.  I work very much like a laboratory and not like a noisy, dusty, carpentry shop.\n\nI got interested in mobile computing as I could see the potential as I walked around NYC seeing how laptops and cell phone technology was evolving and becoming more ingrained into peoples lives.  My dad was a computer scientist so having grown up around the technology it was an interesting way to blend my fine  art background with the science and figure out a way to be involved with something \"big\" in it\'s infancy. Not being a programmer or interested in coding, making rugged, lightweight protective cases for mobile computers has been a good fit.  \n\nRight now I am working on a project for the T.S.A. designing cases for conveyor belt systems to expedite the scanning of laptops.  It is a project with great potential as the T.S.A scans 500 million laptops a year.  Hopefully my work will have an impact on improving peoples lives and safety.','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:08','2016-03-26 00:06:08'),(527,'0014-12-02','Robert','Johnson','','','Under development','','','','Other','','Practicing electrical engineer recently at Bell Labs - Murray Hill, NJ (Alcatel-Lucent) implementing subsections of 3G/4G software defined radios.  I am considered hardware engineer due to my focus on FPGAs (Field Programmable Gate  Arrays).  Essentially self-taught in the field. Undergraduate at Union College BA Interdepartmental Fine Arts / Physics / Photography / Engineering. Master\'s in Industrial Design from Pratt.  \n\nCurrently studying Linux as a first step in getting into back in software where I hope to master a new computer language called OpenCL which allows  FPGAs to act as programmable on-the-fly custom data accelerators to give \"supercomputer-like\" power to low cost PCs to solve complex algorithms. \n\nBut by nature I am a photographer / visualizer / repairer / inventor  who would rather do Good through stealthy means rather than seek credit. I have developed a solution-finding technique where after immersing myself in a problem then, with intentionality, I submit it to my subconscious where often, at an unpredictable time, an eloquent fully formed solution will resurface as if remembering a dream; a solution more rich and elegant, more  synergistic, and surprising than one could have thought their way into through logical sequential  thinking.\n\nI have an attic in my brain of inventions I wish to pursue from a wind rotor concept that uses the shape of the typical ridged roof to focus the wind, to a self-sharpening razor that would not have to be disposed, a creating moving pictures in individually addressable LED Christmas lights adorning trees, to promoting a movie script I wrote, to a \"sun light funnel\" that folds flat but when expanded concentrates light to a small area for several possible solar energy applications.  These are just some of the better ones but everyday I think of micro/macro ways of improving the world and myself.','','','I finally realize that no traditional job will begin to use a fraction of my capabilities due to  the broad range of my interests (not to mention that I probably have ADD where going off on tangents is my specialty). New Jersey has grown very stale. I am 62 but have run twelve NY C Marathons and expect many years of productivity ahead. If I could find a space in which to create, to reify, to drift around planting ideas in others, I think it could benefit Man and me in that order.\n\nP.S.  One of the coolest things I have lately done is located the crash site of a famous aviator Max Miller - the first civilian pilot hired by the then fledgling US Airmail Service.  I heard just yesterday that an article describing my success will be published June \'15 by The Smithsonian\'s \"Air and Space\" magazine.','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:08','2016-03-26 00:06:08'),(528,'0014-11-28','Peter','Strugatz','','','www.strugatzventures.com','','','','Other','','Consultant','','','Please send information.\nThanks,\nPeter','','','','2016-03-26 00:06:08','2016-03-26 00:06:08'),(529,'2016-03-25','Vitor','Freire','vitor.freire@gmail.com','Imagination Of Things','http://imaginationofthings.com','http://imaginationofthings.com/files/portfolio_english.pdf','','Micro: 2-4','Connected Devices','Resident','We use design and technology to create dances for the soul, choreographing human communication. To design live things, we aim for the unexpected, the surprise, the improvisation. It’s a motion- centered attitude, not a skill set.','Use this space if you\'d like to tell us more about your technology','Monique Grimord is an Interactive Designer, prototyping the future, inspired by social connection and building tools for the creative economy. She graduated in Political Science and holds a MFA in Design at the Savannah College of Art & Design.\r\nIn 2014 she worked as an Invention Designer at the Innovation Lab called Room For More Possibilities at Crispin, Porter + Bogusky, where she is still a collaborator.\r\n\r\nVitor Freire is a Brazilian Storyteller and Designer of Social Experiences. He holds a M.P.S at the Interactive Telecommunications Program at NYU. He has over 8+ years of experience directing videos, designing interactive projects and creating relevant content for major brands and social movements.','Anything else you want to share?','Self-Sustaining','Prototyping shops, Event space','Inspire and be inspired, bringing imagination and a little bit of poetry to the Human-Computer Interactions.','2016-03-26 00:09:16','2016-03-26 00:09:16'),(530,'2016-03-24','Seth And Ariane ','Harrison','seth@harrisonatelier.com','Harrison Atelier','www.harrisonatelier.com','www.appletreepartners.com','','Micro: 2-4','Life Sciences','Resident','We create projects about the impact of the life sciences on the built world and culture. We are sophisticated and accomplished in capital raising, business building, teaching, lecturing, mentoring, boardmanship, advising, etc.  We think being part of New Lab would be a cross-fertilizing experience. \r\n','Use this space if you\'d like to tell us more about your technology','Tell us about you and your team','Anything else you want to share?','Self-Sustaining','Prototyping shops, Event space, Conference rooms & breakout spaces, Member Community','Why do you want to be at New Lab?','2016-03-26 00:09:16','2016-03-26 00:09:16'),(531,'2016-03-24','Bram ','De Zwart','bram@3dhubs.com','3D Hubs','https://www.3dhubs.com','https://www.3dhubs.com/about','https://twitter.com/3DHubs','Solo: 1 person','Additive Tech','Resident','Digital manufacturing machines such as 3D printers are becoming the factories of the future. They enable consumer products to be made on­-demand and much closer to their point of purchase, eliminating waste from overproduction and transport. 3D Hubs is accelerating this future by giving everyone direct access to 3D printers','The 3D Hubs online platform provides the easiest way to bring designs to life by offering local 3D print production in under two days. We check the user’s digital design and our matchmaking algorithms present the best 3D print options for them.','3D Hubs was founded in 2013 by Dutch design engineers Bram and Brian. They both started their career at Freedom Of Creation in 2009, the pioneering company that was the first to use 3D printing to create actual end-products. After the acquisition by 3D Systems in 2011 they became involved in the design and launch of their new consumer platform.\r\n\r\nFast-forward to 2015: 3D Hubs has raised $4.5M in investments led by Balderton Capital and expanded the team to 35 people located in New York and Amsterdam.','We\'ve already been a tenant in the New Lab beta space in 2014 and know Scott Cohen well. We\'re only interested in one desk now as most of the team is in Amsterdam but will potentially scale the NY team in the future. ','Venture Funding','Event space, Member Community','Because we\'re both leading brands in this new age of manufacturing ','2016-03-26 00:09:16','2016-03-26 00:09:16'),(532,'2016-03-20','Bernhard','Mehl','bm@getkisi.com','KISI','getkisi.com','','','Medium: 10-30','Connected Devices','Resident','KISI opens doors every day: Kisi\'s physical access control is an ideal match for high turnover, fast growing or multi-location facilities. AngelList, Digital Ocean, Oscar Health and Cushman Wakefield are among the first of our 200 customers who have started controlling their doors like their internet.\r\n','Using every sensor in your smartphone, Kisi leverages the full bandwidth of near-field technologies, cell connectivity and wifi to deliver unlocks on high speed, reliable rate and at great security.','Max, Carl and Bernhard - some call us a hipster, hacker and a hustler. We\'ve all worked in startups before, Max and Bernhard at a high-tech fitness machine startup where we got annoyed by the ringing doorbell. Eventually found out that this is a problem much closer to our heart since everyone carries a key - and there shouldn\'t be a reason for it anymore.','We have a product that works - made in NY and assembled, quality controlled and shipped in Brooklyn. What  we are currently building is the next level of our product infrastructure: Better design, more sensors, easier operations which will allow a variety of new sales channels.','Venture Funding','Prototyping shops, Event space, Conference rooms & breakout spaces, Member Community','We\'ve been in coworking spaces and shared spaces since we\'ve started. Additionally many of our customers are the fastest growing coworking spaces in the US. We know what a good culture is made of and are looking forward to bounce ideas with like-minded hardware folks to brew up some new approaches. In the end we want to help brand Brooklyn to become \"made in Brooklyn\". And we can only do that together.','2016-03-26 00:09:16','2016-03-26 00:09:16'),(533,'2016-03-18','Madison','Maxey','maddy@thecrated.com','The Crated','www.thecrated.com','','','Small: 5-9','Connected Devices','Resident','The Crated is developing a tool kit to help manufacturers produce robust and reliable textile-based wearable tech. Our technology allows manufacturers to deposit conductive ink directly onto fabric for composite architecture, smart safety wear and consumer apparel like heated jackets.','Our technology is both chemical and process oriented. By properly treating fabric and using the right dyes, it\'s possible to make flexible circuits on fabric. ','Madison Maxey founded the Crated in 2013 after receiving the Thiel Fellowship.  Since then, she has  been on Forbes 30 Under 30 List, NBC BLK 28 Under 28, Brooklyn Magazine\'s 30 Under 30 and has been featured in major publications from FastCompany to the Today Show. Her experiences in creative tech include residencies from Autodesk, The School of visual arts and more.','We plan on working with large apparel brands with innovation labs and safety specific factories to license our tech and set up our circuit printing process in a way that\'s suitable for their existing supply chain. ','Venture Funding','Prototyping shops, Event space, Conference rooms & breakout spaces, Member Community','We\'re a group of multidisciplinary and creative designers and technologists that love to make, share and contribute to others.  We look forward to sharing knowledge, lending LEDs and having casual conversations around chemistry as being part of the space.','2016-03-26 00:09:16','2016-03-26 00:09:16'),(534,'2016-03-18','Frank','Luciano','frank@goldbely.com','Goldbely','www.goldbely.com','http://techland.time.com/2013/05/06/50-best-websites-2013/slide/goldbely/','http://www.fastcompany.com/3039976/how-to-make-a-2000-mile-pizza-delivery','Small: 5-9','Additive Tech','Resident','Goldbely helps people find the best food from around the country and have it shipped to their door.  We empower small and medium regional food producers to expand to a national market beyond their usual reach.','Half of our team are developers (including two of our four founders).  We built our entire front and back end systems from scratch.  We\'re building tools for our partners to use on a daily basis to make their lives and business more efficient.  A recent focus for us as a business has been SaaS as an additional benefit for our marketplace partners.','4 Founders\r\nJoel Ariel- CEO- Former CEO of Delivery.com, Founder of EATS Network\r\nTrevor Stow- CTO- Over 20 years of professional development experience\r\nJoel Gillman- Lead Front End Dev- formerly of Blip\r\nVanessa Torrivilla- Head of Product- former lead UX and designer at Blip and BuyWithMe','We\'ve been selling products for nearly 4 years using a combination of free media, word of mouth and minimal paid advertisements.  Our partners are our biggest fans and help us drive sales and acquire customers.  While we were initially venture funded, we are now self sustaining. ','Venture Funding','Event space, Member Community','So much of our business revolves around being a part of the community.  Not only the food community, but also the local communities for each and every one of our partners.  We tell our partners\' stories more than we tell Goldbely\'s; it\'s in properly telling these stories to the rest of the world that will allow us to succeed as a business.  We call ourselves and our community \"Explorers of Food\" so we love the connection that the shipyard has to shipbuilding and travel.  Plus, we always have plenty of the best food in the country on hand to share with our fellow community members :)','2016-03-26 00:09:16','2016-03-26 00:09:16'),(535,'2016-03-18','James','Cazzoli','james@bloominhaler.com','Bloom','bloominhaler.com','','','Micro: 2-4','Life Sciences','Resident','Bloom is a credit-card sized inhaler for asthmatics. It holds 6 doses of emergency medication, and is infinitely refillable using your current prescription. ','Our technology is a patent pending mechanism, which enables the dispensing of precisely metered doses of medication. This technology serves to enable a new form of delivering inhaled medications. We are currently focusing on asthma. ','The team consists of two cofounders and three advisors. \r\n\r\nJames Cazzoli is a mechanical engineer and industrial designer with a degree from Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute. He has worked at Apple and OXO as a design engineer, and at Google as an interaction designer. He holds two patents from both Apple and Google. \r\n\r\nHaimin Yie is a mechanical engineer with a degree from Purdue. He has worked as a design engineer at various consultancies such as Smart Design, Quirky, and TomorrowLab. \r\n\r\nAdvisors:\r\n\r\nDr. Shaker Mousa is the Executive Director at Pharmaceutical Research Institute. Holds 350 patents and has brought multiple billion dollar medications to market. \r\n\r\nMatt Cusack is a seasoned entrepreneur in the energy and medical industries. He founded Plug Power which IPO\'d in 1999. He served as the Entrepreneur in Residence at RPI and Siena College. \r\n\r\nTom Casey has brought multiple medical devices through the FDA (including nebulizers/atomizers)','Direct-to-consumer and indirect-to-consumer. Then licensing.\r\n\r\nDirect: Sales of Bloom and it\'s replacement parts through our website.\r\n\r\nIndirect: Walgreens, CVS, other retail pharmacies.\r\n\r\nLicensing (long term): We may license Bloom to pharmaceutical companies, or work with PRI to create a generic HFA albuterol and sell as a combination product (hardware + medication). TBD','Bootstrap','Prototyping shops','James and Haimin are both talented mechanical engineers with experience in electronics/programming. James has gone through the entrepreneurship track while at 30 Weeks (Google\'s accelerator). We would be happy to provide hardware and design tips to our colleagues. We are also looking to give and receive peer mentorship in this community. ','2016-03-26 00:09:16','2016-03-26 00:09:16'),(536,'2016-03-28','Caroline','Woolard','CarolineWoolard@gmail.com','Caroline Woolard & Lika Volkova','http://carolinewoolard.com','http://nycreic.com','http://www.sans.name/lookbook/ss2009.html','Solo: 1 person','Built Environment','Resident','I build objects, spaces, and organizations for the new economy. Since 2008, I\'ve co-founded four collaborative, resource-sharing groups: OurGoods.org, TradeSchool.coop, BFAMFAPhD.com, and NYCREIC.com. I teach at the New School and SVA and have a documentary coming out about my work from PBS / Art21.','At the moment, I am using kevlar, CNC machines, laser cutters, blown glass, and a yakisugi technique with cedar wood to create furniture, clothing, and a service design that explores the future of the @ symbol. http://carolinewoolard.com/projects/#CarriedOnBothSides','I work with Lika Volkova, a fashion designer, and, at times, glass blowers Helen Lee and Alexander Rosenberg. We were Rome Prize Design finalists for our recent project, Carried on Both Sides. Lika\'s work is here: http://www.sans.name/lookbook/ss2009.html','Depending on the needs and desires of the community, I would be interested in contributing programming / events, including classes on resource-sharing, new economic systems, and pattern-making, sewing, and drafting by Lika Volkova, or any of the programs and events you see at: http://carolinewoolard.com/#events','Grants','Prototyping shops, Event space, Member Community','The new economy needs a new lab. I feel that my work as an artist, scholar, and innovator is best supported by interdisciplinary places, and because I know that this is the milieu in which I am able to contribute most. My recent work, Carried on Both Sides, has been developed over the past few months in New York City and has confirmed research support from the Design Department at MoMA and the Education Department at the Metropolitan Museum of Art, but I need a site of innovation to experiment with materials and to refine my speculative design products. Aiming to communicate across social spheres, I make site-specific projects that circulate in contemporary art and design institutions as well as in urban development and social entrepreneurship settings. As a site of encounter and exchange, New Lab is the place where my thinking and practice will advance most fully.','2016-03-28 06:13:59','2016-03-28 06:13:59'),(537,'2016-03-28','James','Patten','james@pattenstudio.com','Patten Studio','www.pattenstudio.com','https://www.ted.com/talks/james_patten_the_best_computer_interface_maybe_your_hands?language=en','','Small: 5-9','Robotics','Resident','Patten Studio creates novel interactive experiences that go beyond traditional online and screen-based interactions. Combining an expertise in technology, design, and user interaction, we work with clients ranging from global brands to science museums to build experiences that provoke curiosity, invite play, and incite imagination. ','Patten Studio utilizes technology to expand the vocabulary of design, imagining a future where interactive experiences go beyond traditional screen displays, making everyday buildings and spaces even more dynamic and interactive than the online, digital world. We develop interactive technologies that enable new styles of interaction between people and computers.\r\n\r\nFeatured in Fast Company and as a TED talk, Patten Studio’s \'Thumbles\' is a series of small robots that drive around on a tabletop display and serve as tactile representations of on-screen information, engaging the sense of touch to create richer interactions. \r\n\r\nA current internal research project known as \'Black Box\' is a sensor platform designed to track and monitor how people move through spaces to enable new modes of interaction. ','James Patten, Principal - James is an interaction designer, inventor and visual artist working at the intersection of the physical and digital worlds. He earned his PhD in 2006 at the MIT Media Lab. James is a TED Fellow, and his work has been shown at the Museum of Modern Art and recognized in international design competitions.\r\n\r\nMihae S. Mukaida, Creative Director - Mihae is equal parts designer, strategist, and producer. She brings to bear extensive marketing experience working with blue chip brands - conceiving, designing, and executing on experiential campaigns and installations for Intel, DuPont,  AT&T, TED, and L’Oreal.     \r\n\r\nJen Lusker, Operations Manager - Jen brings a unique pairing of skills as both project manager and electrical engineer - overseeing the technical execution of interactive projects as well as printed circuit board designs. Prior to Patten Studio, Jen worked at Shick, a medical devices company,','Established in 2006, Patten Studio operates similarly to other experiential ad agencies, working directly with clients and brands to develop and execute concepts for interactive experiences in support of their goals. Unlike other advertising agencies, our technical expertise allows us to build upon an internal library of reusable interactive technology building blocks (e.g. sensor and motor control circuits) as well as pursue our own independent research projects. This approach allows us to push the boundaries of interactivity through new technologies and techniques. ','Self-Sustaining','Prototyping shops, Conference rooms & breakout spaces, Member Community','The interdisciplinary nature of our work means that we work best when engaged with a community of groups with a wide range of expertise. Our commitment to this work style is illustrated by our participation in the community at 33 Flatbush Ave. Together with Terreform, Patten Studio founded the community now known as Dark Matter in 2009. The model behind this space is one of informal collaboration and shared knowledge and tools. We already have close ties with many groups at the Beta space, and have a deep understanding of the kind of structure and engagement needed to keep a community like that thriving. We bring to the table a mix of expertise in various fields of engineering and design as well as a desire to learn from and collaborate with others. We have a variety of specialized tools that we’re happy to share with those who use them responsibly. \r\n','2016-03-29 01:36:56','2016-03-29 01:36:56'),(538,'2016-03-30','Adam','Leeb','adam@astrohaus.com','Adam@astrohaus.com','astrohaus.com','https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/adamleeb/hemingwrite-a-distraction-free-digital-typewriter/description ','adamleeb.com','Micro: 2-4','Connected Devices','Resident','Astrohaus is the product development team behind the Freewrite, the world\'s first smart typewriter. We are a lean team of passionate entrepreneurs that don\'t take anything for granted, especially conventional design paradigms. Astrohaus is a vehicle for us to build products that focus on the merging of design and utility.','Straightforward in appearance, the device incorporates the latest technology available including a 1 ghz custom embedded linux platform using a Freescale MX6 processor. We chose to use an E Ink screen that provides a great experience to the user in spite of the huge challenge of working with a closed product with very limited available support. The software is tightly integrated with our hardware platform and can be updated over-the-air with our internally developed update service. ','Patrick and I (Adam) are the Cofounders of Astrohaus. We met in an incubator in Detroit while passionately discussing writing process and the potential for a physical device to mimic the capabilities of distraction-free writing software. Both of us are hugely opinionated doers that think about our everyday lives and how we can make things better. Patrick is a talented software developer while I do product design and oversee production. At the end of 2015, we added two other talented member to our team, Charlie Weikert, who comes to us from Rolls Royce as a mechanical engineer and Steph Kent, who comes from the Wall Street Journal and TED to be our Community Director.','Referral from Manuel Toscano. ','Angel Funding','Prototyping shops, Event space, Conference rooms & breakout spaces, Member Community','The opening of New Lab comes at a great time because our small team is actively looking for a home. We arrived to NYC from Detroit in August of last year and found some great temporary space but it was never the perfect fit. Since we started Astrohaus, we have always wanted to find a place with proper facilities and the right community. We are anxious to join a community that gives us the freedom to do what we do while providing a great environment for collaboration. I think our team would tick all the boxes of companies and people that you are looking to include in your space: we are a growth stage company (well funded) with interesting people that are making a \'connected device\' product which shows well. We\'d also hope to contribute to the group by promoting New Lab and being awesome members!','2016-03-30 12:19:21','2016-03-30 12:19:21'),(539,'2016-03-31','ANANTH','SAMPATHKUMAR','ananthrobert@ndny.co','NDNY ARCHITECTURE + DESIGN','www.ndny.co','','','Micro: 2-4','Built Environment','Resident','NDNY (New Delhi | New York) is a bespoke architecture + design practice with trans-continental aspirations. We strive to make our built interventions more responsive, reactive, socially and ecologically sustainable and engaged with its surroundings. We have been fortunate to work in the US, Srilanka, India and Israel. ','We have tried to push the design and delivery process by harnessing the power of digital design and fabrication tools including BIM, parametric modelling, laser cutting, plasma and CNC cutting. We hope to avail of any new facilities at Newlab to explore new techniques for design and construction.','My partner Mary Chandrahasan and I started this practice 3 years ago on a part-time basis. It is now more than a full-time gig. Our work has grown from modest restaurant and residential projects to larger institutional and commercial endeavors. We try and maintain a sense of purpose, design and environmental/social responsibility in all our work. We are both licensed architects with over 13 years of experience, having worked for Richard Meier and Partners, Robert Stern Architects, Gensler and FX Fowle. Since arriving in the US, over 15 years ago, we have worked hard to build our own trajectory and are looking for new ways to keep it moving upward. Collaboration is a big part of our manifesto and the work environment at Newlab would be provide the ideal milieu for new adventures. We hope we can bring a unique perspective to the table at Newlab!','Thank you for considering us for Newlab. The creative and entrepreneurial spirit that defined the first collaborative setup at Navy Yards has been a huge inspiration for us. We hope we can be part of Newlab and bring something unique to the place.','Bootstrap','Prototyping shops, Event space, Conference rooms & breakout spaces','I visited the previous version of Newlab in which Terraform 1 and The Living were housed. The intense collaborative environment and the eventual cross pollination of ideas made me sign up to be part of the new development. ','2016-04-01 19:59:22','2016-04-01 19:59:22'),(540,'2016-03-30','Abigail','Edgecliffe-Johnson','abigail@raceya.com','RaceYa','raceya.com','facebook.com/raceyatoys','https://twitter.com/RaceYaToys','Micro: 2-4','Robotics','Resident','RaceYa uses customizable, programmable, radio-controlled cars to teach kids about STEM.\r\nWe are fostering a community of curious kids, starting with a race-able science kit\r\nand expanding out into an immersive universe of customization, education and collaboration.','Use this space if you\'d like to tell us more about your technology','Abigail Edgecliffe-Johnson is the founder of RaceYa. She has a PhD in Anthropology as well as many years of experience as a Maker and Tinkerer. She has spent the past 8 years using her research chops to understand how and why kids play and learn the way they do.\r\n\r\nOmar Kiyani is in charge of RaceYa’s product execution. He has extensive hardware experience from Applied Materials and Cisco and has an MS in Electrical Engineering from Columbia University.','Anything else you want to share?','Bootstrap','Prototyping shops, Member Community','We\'re passionate about our work, but not as experienced as we\'d like to be. It would be valuable to be within a community of other hardware makers to bounce ideas off of, learn from and collaborate with. ','2016-04-01 19:59:22','2016-04-01 19:59:22'),(541,'2016-04-03','Brett','Zaccardi','brett@streetattack.com','Street Attack','www.streetattack.com','https://vimeo.com/user996222 ','http://www.nolongerempty.org/','Micro: 2-4','Built Environment','Resident','I\'m responding to an email from Scott Cohen. I\'ve been watching NewLab intently for a few years and am very excited about what I\'ve seen evolve here and in the Navy Yard. \r\n\r\nStreet Attack combines urban environments, technology and creativity with an eye on 4D user experience and engagement. ','We develop proprietary technology to enhance user engagement. We also utilize stacks of technology that evolve already existing frameworks. We believe cities are living organisms and the prevalence of connectivity has created a whole new marketplace for experiences. There are a number of products and IP in development which address these subjects of New Urbanism and Smart Cities. We\'re also a functioning agency that promotes technology and awareness for other clients. In short we\'re Voltron for Art, Ideas and Technology.  We can benefit inventors, dreamers technologists and the like by promoting awareness and access to clients and projects that can achieve proof of concept and short term funding. ','Our external work is project based and thus utilizes project teams, producers and specialists mostly in the field. \r\nOur internal work is around strategy, technology and business ideas. Thus we have a nimble team of dev/coding, strat and growth. We often work with artists so they may be present for days or weeks depending on project life cycles.    ','\"Unexpected invitations to travel are like dancing lessons from god\" - Kurt Vonnegut ','Self-Sustaining','Prototyping shops, Event space, Conference rooms & breakout spaces, Member Community','New innovative space inspiring ideas inventions and creativity. ','2016-04-03 20:35:03','2016-04-03 20:35:03'),(542,'2016-04-01','James','Clar','james@jamesclar.com','James Clar LLC','www.JamesClar.com','','','Micro: 2-4','Connected Devices','Resident','I\'m a conceptual media artist working on various scales; from individual sculptural artworks to large permanent building installations. My work has been exhibited at various galleries, museums, and technology art fairs; Wired NextFest, NHK Digista, New Museum, PS1 MoMA, etc.','I use a broad range of technology within my work, a large portion of which is light sculptures. These use LEDs, 3D printed parts (many of them produced at New Labs), and Raspberry Pi or other controllers. High definition cameras, 4k Televisions, projectors. etc. I\'m currently working on a large scale installation for 21c Museum Hotels in Oklahoma that uses conveyor belts to create a dynamic morphing installation that also displays the time. Another large installation was done at Frankfurt Airport, which was an 8 story tall light installation that reacted to sound.  Sometimes I use off-the-shelf parts but other times custom made circuits or controllers will be made for specific effects. ','I have a network of colleagues that I will work with depending on the project. Things will scale up as needed or sometimes I just work on a solo sculpture myself. There are generally around 3 - 5 works constantly in production.','Anything else you want to share?','Self-Sustaining','Prototyping shops','I\'ve been going to New Labs a lot over the last couple years. I went to ITP (class of 2003) so I know a few people at NewLabs already. I\'m good friends with Jason Krugman. Also, a lot of my 3D printing production is done at New Labs.  I think the environment is great for developing new concepts with technology.  It\'d be great to be part of this experimental scene and contribute to it!','2016-04-03 20:35:03','2016-04-03 20:35:03'),(543,'2016-04-06','Emily','Wheeler','ewheeler@smartergridsolutions.com','Smarter Grid Solutions Inc.','www.Smartergridsolutions.com','http://www.smartergridsolutions.com/us/products/anm-strata-maximize-benefit-from-der/','https://twitter.com/SmrtrGridSols','Medium: 10-30','Energy','Resident Urban Tech','Smarter Grid Solutions has spent ten years developing, deploying and proving our approach to managing the\r\nSmart Grid. We are recognized as thought leaders in this domain and have worked with and learned from electricity\r\ndistribution companies, regulatory authorities, university research teams, DER developers, SCADA/DMS suppliers,\r\ngrid edge device manufacturers and many others.','ANM is a unique distributed energy resource management system (DERMS) for electric distribution operators (utilities). ANM uses real-time functionality to manage and control the operation of DER and other grid edge devices. It is the ONLY DERMS solution to feature fast-acting response, guaranteed time bounding, adequate fail safes and predictable operation.\r\n\r\nUnlike other DERMS solutions, we do not rely on a network model, forecasting, and load flow analysis techniques. That means our DERMS solution delivers:\r\n\r\nGreater DER hosting capacity\r\nReduced time and cost to implement\r\nReduced cost to support and maintain\r\nTransparent operation to ease adoption and acceptance\r\nOperators with a simple and clear understanding of how the system operates\r\nDER customers with a clear and auditable view of their grid connection\r\nSecond by second view of DER status and operation','In 2008, Smarter Grid Solutions was formed to offer a new type of autonomous time-bounded distribution control system to complement existing utility systems, specifically targeted at renewable energy integration challenges.  The company has grown to over 60 employees (37 Bachelors, 19 Masters and 8 PhDs) spread across the UK (Glasgow and London) and North America (New York, San Fran and Calgary) providing power systems analysis, software development, solutions delivery and support.\r\n\r\nSGS operates in North America, through a subsidiary Smarter Grid Solutions Inc. The Bob Currie, Chief Technical Officer and Co-Founder is responsible for all Technology Development within the company. Bob is based in the Brooklyn office and is the Executive leading SGS activities in NA. Bob is joined by Emily Wheeler, VP of Operations, two Senior Engineers, one Senior Analyst and one admin.  The team will soon be joined by a Senior Technology Lead, PM and Smart Grid Engineer.','Referred by Simon Sylvester-Chaudhuri ','Venture Funding','Conference rooms & breakout spaces','We\'d like to have space to build out our hardware in. Raised floor, rack space, AC, power source, etc. ','2016-04-06 22:30:02','2016-04-06 22:30:02'),(544,'2016-04-08','Justin','Meltzer','justin@novoreality.com','Novo','novoreality.com','https://drive.google.com/file/d/0B36ZG1-zl5BzVm1Xbl84a0o1clU/view?usp=sharing','','Small: 5-9','Robotics','Resident','Novo is creating a world-class motion simulation platform for premium cinematic virtual reality experiences. We believe unrestricted motion, which is lacking in home VR experiences, will be one of the most critical tools in premium VR storytelling. This is cinema 2.0 and represents the future of out-of-the-home entertainment.','We are using state-of-the-art robotic arm motion simulators (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XjSN4fWemxE) and the latest virtual reality head mounted displays running on the most powerful NVIDIA graphics cards to create the highest quality virtual reality ride experience ever. The physical motion of the simulator is precisely synchronized with the movement of the virtual camera in the VR experience. We use motion in a sophisticated way to unfold the drama of the story\'s plot by directing attention and conveying tone, rather than just to simply provide a thrilling ride experience.','Justin Meltzer (http://bit.ly/23iCcdU) - CEO - Serial entrepreneur and summa cum laude graduate from the Wharton business school. Started my last company while in college and sold it to Pegasystems, a public company. Experience with business, operations, production management, and software engineering.\r\n\r\nJordan Harvey (http://bit.ly/1YjA3Yw) - Chief Creative Officer - Brilliant creative and technical director. Over 10+ years\' experience in CG within the advertising industry crafting compelling and beautiful short form content. Virtual reality specialist for the past 3 years, leading many of the first high profile VR experiences launched by bluechip brands.\r\n\r\nStephen Sywak (http://bit.ly/1XlLYF9) - Chief Engineer - Mechanical engineer with over 25+ years\' experience in entertainment engineering industry. Specializes in large dynamic structures and worked on an immense number of high profile projects for leading entertainment companies, including Disney, Cirque du Soleil, Universal Studios, etc.','We\'re the most passionate, enthusiastic, ambitious, and talented team that you\'ll find anywhere. We have a killer idea.','Bootstrap','Prototyping shops, Event space, Conference rooms & breakout spaces, Member Community','The focus on hardware is very attractive to us. We will fit right into a community of talented and dedicated professionals working on cutting edge hardware that push the limits of what technology can do.\r\n\r\nNew Lab\'s large space with high ceilings is critical as we\'ll be working with robots that require a minimum of 25 feet in clearance height.','2016-04-09 01:09:40','2016-04-09 01:09:40'),(545,'2016-04-13','Marshall','Cox','marshall@radiatorlabs.com','Radiator Labs','www.radiatorlabs.com','','','Solo: 1 person','Connected Devices','Resident Urban Tech','\r\nRadiator Labs eliminates overheating in the millions of steam-heated housing units across the United States, while granting temperature control to inhabitants for the first time in the history of these buildings.','The Radiator Labs mission is to use a systems-based thermodynamic approach to solving the overheating problem in millions of overheated homes across the United States and abroad. By incorporating single radiator-level control with real-time data visualization of the whole-building environment, we can eliminate billions in waste fuel consumption, all while increasing comfort for tenants and granting them temperature control for the first time in the history of our aging building stock.','All Star!','Anything else you want to share?','Angel Funding','Prototyping shops, Event space, Conference rooms & breakout spaces, Member Community','We work very closely with Marcel Botha at 10xBeta, we\'ve known about the space for a while, and we\'ll have the majority of our team in Building 3 as part of Startup New York. We\'d love to have access to the New Lab and to be part of the community.','2016-04-13 23:43:46','2016-04-13 23:43:46'),(546,'2016-04-13','Marissa','Schuchat','marissa.schuchat@my.liu.edu','Wi-Move, Inc.','http://liuhack.wix.com/sensor','http://devpost.com/software/wi-move','https://drive.google.com/open?id=0B8SxN0-njJvMa0lfTWpUYXRuZ1U','Small: 5-9','Urban Tech','Resident Urban Tech','We are a student team who has a solution to the congested Downtown Brooklyn Free Wi-Fi network. Our idea is to broaden the reach of the existing network via the wearable Wi-Move sensor. We want to build a working prototype that will serve the needs of the community. ','The Downtown Brooklyn area is experiencing a population boom, and with that comes stress on the infrastructure. The existing Wi-Fi network, aided by FON routers, is not sufficiently handling the load. We want to essentially build a mobile Wi-Fi repeater, thereby extending the coverage area of the existing network. In a civic capacity this is typically done by installing Wi-Fi capability in fixed places, such as garbage cans and utility poles, but we want to capitalize on the physical activity (biking, walking, dog-walking, pushing strollers) of the citizens on the street. A similar concept was tried in San Francisco called Free the Net, and successfully so, by a company called Meraki. Their user base grew from 20,000 to 100,000 in one year\'s time, and the project ended not because of failure, but because they were acquired by Cisco. Brooklynites enjoy being outside, and this is something they would benefit from.','We are a diverse mix of Computer Science students and Marketers. Consisting of two Caucasians, three Latinos, and two African-Americans (3 females, 4 males) we are the embodiment of the research findings of what a successful team looks like. Myself and my co-founder, Reymont Proano, have worked together on various CS projects, and he is the current on-campus IT manager. I have a breadth of technology experience, and a strong interest in wearables. We would like to add more tech talent, including an advisor, to this pursuit. The remaining members are dedicated Business students who created beautiful marketing collateral in a very short time. They created the logo and copy writing, collected valuable external validation, and would be an asset to the project. ','After pitching recently at the BE.IN Hack Brooklyn Innovation Challenge, the first judge\'s remark was: \"forget the competition, go out and do it, it\'s a great idea, make it fast.\" We wound up winning this competition and feel empowered to move forward and execute on the idea. On the tech side, we are very passionate about technology and hardware hacking. As graduating students, we could really benefit from the technical knowledge of the New Lab community, and would be honored to work in this great space. ','Bootstrap','Prototyping shops','We\'ve spent years in the Downtown Brooklyn area as students and interns, and we are excited a facility like this exists so close by. For our purposes, New Lab is perfect. New Lab offers the exact resources we need to get Wi-Move off the ground. The combination of machinery and resources, both mechanical and human, is unlike anyplace we have ever been in the borough. We would be proud to develop in this space and contribute locally. We see New Lab as a place that is about empowering the community, which includes students. New Lab\'s proximity to our school and others makes it desirable to stay in the area and push the boundaries. New Lab represents an opportunity for those of us who want to make a difference through technology.','2016-04-13 23:43:46','2016-04-13 23:43:46'),(547,'2016-04-14','Robert','Steiner','rob@roboto.nyc','Roboto.NYC','Roboto.nyc','https://www.linkedin.com/in/robert-steiner-a4b19a5','','Micro: 2-4','Additive Tech','Resident','CAD (Solidworks), Design for 3D Printing expert(s) including iMaterialise Magics, Printing & Post processing.   Primarily focused on fabrication of prototypes, project management (for 3D printing), fulfillment, Machine Maintenance (MakerBot, Solidscape, Connex/Objet).  Extensive experience in program and project management.\r\n\r\nWorking with Artists, designers, companies, startups.','From Art to Part - taking a concept or idea and moving it through the maturation process using latest in technology and old school artistic effort.','Rob Steiner:                Former MakerBot Chief Product Officer, 30 years experience in a variety of industries.\r\nProject Manager:       Industrial Designer, former MakerBot Design Studio Manager.  Post processing expert (assembly, paint, casting)\r\nEngineering Manager:  Mechanical Engineer with 1:1 experience designing 3D Printers, extruders and associated auxillary equipment. ','Would be interested in having a company internally at the New Lab - that can provide prototyping services (in the new lab shop) or develop/manage an outside provider network.  I excel at networking and mentoring/coaching people through product development.\r\n\r\nHave $200K in funding ready - looking for the right location to set up operations.  Open to purchasing/installing additional capabilities in shop space.\r\n\r\n','Bootstrap','Prototyping shops, Member Community','Currently live in DUMBO -  have been looking for something in the Navy Yard for awhile.\r\n\r\nOpen to discuss a solution to help both of us grow.','2016-04-15 01:14:05','2016-04-15 01:14:05'),(548,'2016-04-13','John','Edgar','john@stae.co','Stae.co','stae.co','fortune.com/2016/04/06/who-owns-the-data/','techcrunch.com/2016/04/04/stae-wants-to-prepare-cities-for-the-future/','Micro: 2-4','Urban Tech','Resident','We\'re building a data platform for the connected city! ','API + data management platform for cities, allowing them to set down minimum data integration points for the private sector. ','https://www.linkedin.com/in/dnsroot\r\nhttps://www.linkedin.com/in/ericschoffstall\r\nhttps://www.linkedin.com/in/andrealmhansen','We\'re in the Urban-X accelerator and working with BMW and SOSv. ','Venture Funding','Conference rooms & breakout spaces, Member Community','We want to be the data for all connected devices working in cities, we believe that mission fits in well with the work you\'re doing. ','2016-04-15 01:14:05','2016-04-15 01:14:05'),(549,'2016-04-15','Vivek','Kumar','vak1000@gmail.com','NangioTx, Inc','http://www.nangiotx.com/NangioTx.html','','','Solo: 1 person','Life Sciences','Resident','NangioTx is developing a regenerative technology to return blood flow to dying organs. Reduced blood flow (ischemia) in peripheral artery disease ultimately results in limb amputation/death. Our flagship technology, V-10, is an injectable hydrogel that rapidly creates new blood vessels. Currently we are doing a 2MM Series A raise.','V-10 is an injectable peptide that self-assembles into a hydrogel in the body where it directs the formation of new blood vessels. V-10 is the product of over a decade of basic science and translational research at Rice University. V-10 utilizes patent pending “biomimicry” to selectively regenerate robust and mature blood vessels. V-10 is delivered by a simple syringe injection and is fast acting, with blood vessels and enhancement of blood flow of limbs in aged/ geriatric (8 month and 13 month old) mice in just 7 days. We have a target molecule, formulation, and have demonstrated efficacy. We have ADME-Tox and CMC studies left prior to human clinical trials.','NangioTx is led by Vivek Kumar, PhD (CEO and co-founder) who have over a decade of experience in regenerative medicine and biomaterials. Vivek developed V-10 along with co-founder and CTO Jeff Hartgerink. Vivek is a professor of biomedical engineering at New Jersey Institute of Technology. Vivek has over 25 peer reviewed publications all in tissue engineering and regenerative medicine.\r\nJeffrey Hartgerink (CTO and co-founder) is a professor of chemistry and bioengineering at Rice University, who have over 80 publications in synthetic chemistry and regenerative medicine. Jeff along with Vivek developed V-10 and have established pre-clinical efficacy.\r\nKarel Petrak (CSO) is a seasoned pharma veteran of over 25 years. He leads NangioTx\' efforts in preclinical development of V-10 for CMC, ADME-Tox studies and non-dilutive funding opportunities.\r\nNangioTx scientific advisory board is composed of Professor Elliot Chaikof MD, PhD (BIDMC, Harvard Medical School), Joseph Mills (BCM), Richard Dixon (THI).','Anything else you want to share?','Bootstrap','Event space, Conference rooms & breakout spaces, Member Community','NangioTx looks to move into the NYC bio-sphere with a focus on our 2MM Series A raise. We are highly motivated by the success of the companies that have been associated with New Lab and were referred to apply by Nicole McKnight.','2016-04-15 22:23:29','2016-04-15 22:23:29'),(550,'2016-04-15','Idan','Cohen','idan@growyes.com','Grow','growyes.com','','','Micro: 2-4','Connected Devices','Resident','We\'re making it easy and hassle free to grow vegetables in your backyard, utilizing an all-in-one smart modular garden system while reimagining the local food production ecosystem.','We\'re designing and manufacturing sensor equipped self watering grow planters that create a mesh network and report soil and environmental conditions back to our servers in order to optimize watering and customer involvement.','We\'re all experienced entrepreneurs having consumer HW startups before and launched products that touched the hands of millions of people.','Love New Lab','Angel Funding','Prototyping shops, Member Community','It sounds like the right environment for a company like ours making high quality consumer HW and SW services that will change the food industry and city landscape.','2016-04-15 23:38:48','2016-04-15 23:38:48'),(551,'2016-04-18','Zach','Lieberman','zach@yesyesno.com','YesYesNo','yesyesno.com','https://vimeo.com/26778535','','Small: 5-9','Urban Tech','Resident','Yesyesno creates intera